{"title_page": "Death Grips", "text_new": "{{short description|American experimental hip-hop band}}\n{{about|the hip hop band|other uses|Death grip (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Death Grips\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = File:Death grips 2014.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Death Grips in January 2014; from left to right: [[Zach Hill]], [[MC Ride]], and Andy Morin\n| origin           = [[Sacramento, California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Experimental hip hop]]\n* [[industrial hip hop]]\n* [[electropunk]]\n* [[noise music|noise]]\n* [[digital hardcore]]\n* [[rap rock]]\n* [[punk rap]]\n<!--Do not remove any genres without consulting the Talk page.-->\n}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* Third Worlds\n* [[Harvest Records|Harvest]]\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n* [[Deathbomb Arc]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hella (band)|Hella]]\n* [[The I.L.Y's]]\n* [[Bj\u00f6rk]]\n* [[Andrew Adamson]]\n* [[Justin Chancellor]]\n* [[Justice Yeldham]]\n* [[Nervous Cop]]\n* [[Tera Melos]]\n* [[Karen Black]]\n* [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]]\n* [[Nine Inch Nails]] \n* [[Les Claypool]]\n* [[Kevin Martin (British musician)|Kevin Martin]]\n}}\n| website          = {{url|thirdworlds.net}}\n| current_members  = \n* [[Jesus Christ | MC Ride]]\n* [[Titanic | Zach Hill]]\n* Andy Morin\n}}\n\n'''Death Grips''' is an American [[experimental hip hop]] band formed in 2010 in [[Sacramento, California]]. The group consists of [[MC Ride]] (vocals, lyrics), [[Zach Hill]] (drums, producing), and Andy Morin (keyboards, producing).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/840695825042886656|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518235919/https://mobile.twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/840695825042886656|archivedate=2017-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|title=Suspicious Minds \u2013 The Resolute Mission Of Death Grips|work=Clash Magazine|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225328/http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Though he is not the band's frontman, Hill has been credited with being the driving creative force behind the project.<ref>https://twitter.com/andy__morin/status/908789368424296448</ref> Their sound, paired with Ride's aggressive performing style, draws on [[punk rock]], [[electronic music|electronic]], [[noise music|noise]], and [[industrial music|industrial]] styles.\n\nThe band released the mixtape ''[[Exmilitary]]'' in April 2011 and their debut studio album, ''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'', almost exactly one year later; both received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/death-grips|title=Death Grips' Scores|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105223159/http://www.metacritic.com/person/death-grips|archivedate=2012-11-05}}</ref> Shortly after signing to [[Epic Records]] in 2012, the group leaked their second album, ''[[No Love Deep Web]]'', for free download in breach of their contract and were dropped from the label. They released their third album, ''[[Government Plates]]'', in 2013. Following several broken performance commitments, the group announced their \"disbanding\" in July 2014 along with the release of their fourth album ''[[The Powers That B]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/784134414965073/?type=1&theater|title=Death Grips \u2013 Timeline Photos \u2013 Facebook|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802170305/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/784134414965073/?type=1&theater|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest |title=\u00e1\u017d eath \u00e1?\u0160rips (@bbpoltergiest) &#124; Twitter |website=Web.archive.org |date=2014-12-10 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210051214/https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest |archivedate=December 10, 2014 }}</ref> However, in March 2015, the group revealed that they \"might make some more\" music<ref name=\"facebook.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/928842713827575 |title=Death Grips \u2013 you're right, we might make some more |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227193323/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/928842713827575 |archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> and later announced a world tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/931696033542243/?type=1&theater |title=Death Grips \u2013 Timeline Photos |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804163952/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/931696033542243/?type=1&theater |archivedate=2016-08-04 }}</ref>\n\nLater in 2015, Death Grips announced their fifth official studio album, ''[[Bottomless Pit (album)|Bottomless Pit]]'', which was released in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/1043779955667183 |title=Death Grips \u2013 We've decided to make a new Death Grips... |publisher=Facebook |date=2015-10-21 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204134209/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/1043779955667183 |archivedate=2017-02-04 }}</ref> Their sixth studio album, ''[[Year of the Snitch]]'', was released in June 2018. Their fourth EP, ''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'', was released in June 2019 in celebration of [[Warp Records]]\u2019 30th anniversary.\n\n==History==\n===2010\u20132011: Formation and ''Exmilitary''===\nDeath Grips were formed in [[Sacramento, California]], on December 21, 2010.<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> On the same day, they recorded their first song, \"Full Moon (Death Classic)\".<ref name=DeathGripsFirstInterview>{{cite web |url=http://www.deathgrips.in/interviews/the-first-interview-fucking-hater/ |title=Death Grips. The First Interview |date=2011-07-27 |accessdate=2014-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015180704/http://www.deathgrips.in/interviews/the-first-interview-fucking-hater/ |archivedate=2014-10-15 }}</ref> It was released on March 8, 2011, with a video and a [[Death Grips (EP)|free self-titled EP]] which featured the song alongside five other songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Full Moon (Death Classic) video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sFmZ6WDkuj0|accessdate=4 November 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405103122/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sFmZ6WDkuj0|archivedate=5 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Death Grips EP|publisher=[[Discogs]]|url=http://www.discogs.com/Death-Grips-Death-Grips/release/3443313|accessdate=2015-04-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150305155603/http://www.discogs.com/Death-Grips-Death-Grips/release/3443313|archivedate=2015-03-05}}</ref> On April 25, 2011, Death Grips released a free mixtape entitled ''[[Exmilitary]]'', containing three tracks from the EP along with new songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Death Grips \u2013 Exmilitary review|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|publisher=Drowned in Sound|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080412/http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Suspicious Minds \u2013 The Resolute Mission Of Death Grips|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|publisher=Clash Music|accessdate=4 November 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003035424/http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|archivedate=3 October 2012}}</ref> Throughout the spring and early summer in 2011, they played small shows while ''Exmilitary'' was spreading steadily throughout the Internet and receiving favorable reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite web|last=Patrin|first=Nate|title=Death Grips \u2013 Exmilitary \u2013 Album Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15583-exmilitary/|publisher=Pitchfork|date=2011-06-30|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127013644/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15583-exmilitary/|archivedate=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Calvert|first=John|title=Death Grip \u2013 Exmilitary Review|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|publisher=Drowned in Sound|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080412/http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> The band members were largely elusive during this time, with the only confirmed member being Hill.<ref name = DeathGripsFirstInterview/>\n\n===2012: ''The Money Store'' and ''No Love Deep Web''===\n[[File:Death Grips Performing in NYC.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Death Grips performing in [[New York City]] in November 2012|right]]\nDeath Grips signed with [[Epic Records]] in February 2012, under the recommendation of Epic's then-executive vice president of marketing, [[Angelica Cob-Baehler]].<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> They announced the release of two albums in 2012. Their first studio album, ''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'', was released in April and debuted on the [[Billboard 200]] chart at No. 130.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/death-grips|title=Death Grips|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> Termed as \"avant-rap\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-money-store-mw0002325196|title=The Money Store \u2013 Death Grips {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] called ''The Money Store'' \"confrontational, abrasive, and chaotic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16512-death-grips-the-money-store/|title=Death Grips: The Money Store Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"punk rock with a hip-hop face-lift\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2012/04/album-review-death-grips-the-money-store.html|title=Album review: Death Grips' 'The Money Store'|date=2012-04-24|website=LA Times Blogs \u2013 Pop & Hiss|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOctober saw the release of ''[[No Love Deep Web]]''. It was described as a darker album by ''[[NPR]]'', saying that the group creates a \"soundtrack to modern urban living\" with lyrics that describe \"constant paranoia\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/bestmusic2012/2012/12/05/166230912/npr-musics-50-favorite-albums-of-2012|title=NPR Music's 50 Favorite Albums Of 2012|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en}}</ref> The album contains heavily edited vocal performances from Ride.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/no-love-deep-web-mw0002434684|title=No Love Deep Web \u2013 Death Grips {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> Its cover art drew attention and controversy for consisting of a picture of Hill's erect penis with the album title written across it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/48035-listen-to-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-now/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003232535/https://pitchfork.com/news/48035-listen-to-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-now/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-10-03|title=Listen to Death Grips' Album NO LOVE DEEP WEB Now, Check Out the Extremely Graphic Cover Art {{!}} News {{!}} Pitchfork|date=2012-10-03|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2012/10/album-review-death-grips-no-love-deep-web/|title=Album Review: Death Grips \u2013 NO LOVE DEEP WEB|date=2012-10-18|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/hpwx/|title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Death Grips \u2013 No Love Deep Web|last=Doran|first=John|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/01/arts/music/new-albums-throwing-muses-death-grips-the-knells-psapp.html|title=New Albums: Throwing Muses, Death Grips, the Knells, Psapp|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=2013-11-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The album was recorded within four months in Sacramento.<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> Prior to that, an international tour was scheduled to support ''The Money Store'', but was immediately cancelled in order to complete ''No Love Deep Web.'' This caused conflict between the group and their fans, as well as their label Epic Records.<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\" /> In particular, the album was self-released for legal download via [[BitTorrent]] as an effort to bypass their label's original intent to release the album in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083590/death-grips-top-bittorrents-list-of-most-legally-downloaded-music|title=Death Grips Top BitTorrent's List of Most Legally Downloaded Music|author=Van Buskirk, Eliot|date=October 1, 2012|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813203441/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083590/death-grips-top-bittorrents-list-of-most-legally-downloaded-music|archivedate=August 13, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/06/public-enemy-bittorrent-bundle-chuck-d-death-grips-p2p-free-download/|title=Public Enemy and Death Grips Use New BitTorrent Bundle to Connect With Fans|author=Raymond, Adam K.|date=June 21, 2013|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827034120/https://www.spin.com/2013/06/public-enemy-bittorrent-bundle-chuck-d-death-grips-p2p-free-download/|archivedate=August 27, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/death-grips/66397|title=Death Grips defy their label with free album release \u2013 listen|date=October 1, 2012|publisher=[[NME]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613051119/http://www.nme.com/news/death-grips/66397|archivedate=June 13, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> Death Grips was cut from their recording contract as a result,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474346/death-grips-dropped-by-epic-following-album-leak|title=Death Grips Dropped By Epic Records Following Album Leak|last=Stutz|first=Colin|date=2012-11-02|work=Billboard|accessdate=2012-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220125625/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474346/death-grips-dropped-by-epic-following-album-leak|archivedate=2016-12-20|url-status=live|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc}}</ref> and would launch their new label Third Worlds in the following year from \"a unique relationship with [[Harvest Records|Harvest]]/[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\u201d. Material would then be distributed by [[Caroline Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/51428-death-grips-launch-new-label-thirdworlds-for-new-album-out-in-2014/|title=Death Grips Launch New Label Third Worlds|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=July 8, 2013|work=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710150543/http://pitchfork.com/news/51428-death-grips-launch-new-label-thirdworlds-for-new-album-out-in-2014/|archivedate=July 10, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe band remixed two [[Bj\u00f6rk]] songs from her album [[Biophilia (album)|''Biophilia'']], \"Sacrifice\" and \"Thunderbolt\", after receiving an artist-to-artist note of support.<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\" /> The re-workings were featured in her 2012 remix album ''[[Bastards (Bj\u00f6rk album)|Bastards]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/z4nv/|title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Bj\u00f6rk \u2013 Bastards|last=Diver|first=Mike|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> A non-album track titled \"True Vulture Bare\" was issued in October 2012 and was accompanied with an animated video by Galen Pehrson. This project was created for the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/48248-new-death-grips-trackvideo-true-vulture/|title=New Death Grips Track/Video: \"True Vulture\" {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132015: ''Government Plates'' and ''The Powers That B''===\n[[File:Death Grips 2013.jpg|thumb|240px|Death Grips performing in [[Moscow]] in May 2013|left]]\nIn March 2013, the band released a series of videos to their [[YouTube]] account, collectively called ''No Hands''. On March 20, 2013, a music video for \"Lock Your Doors\", which was recorded at a live show in [[SXSW]], was released.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/50035-watch-death-grips-share-disorienting-lock-your-doors-video-explain-no-hands-series/ | title=Watch: Death Grips Share Disorienting \"Lock Your Doors\" Video, Explain \"No Hands\" Series | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=March 20, 2013 | accessdate=August 22, 2013 | author=Battan, Carrie | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323002533/http://pitchfork.com/news/50035-watch-death-grips-share-disorienting-lock-your-doors-video-explain-no-hands-series/ | archivedate=March 23, 2013 }}</ref> Hill did not attend the show physically, but played the drums via [[Skype]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spin.com/2013/03/death-grips-lock-your-doors-no-hands-video-sxsw/ | title=See Death Grips' Disorienting Head-Cam and Skype-Shot 'Lock Your Doors' | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=March 20, 2013 | accessdate=August 22, 2013 | author=Marthins, Chris | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020140831/https://www.spin.com/2013/03/death-grips-lock-your-doors-no-hands-video-sxsw/ | archivedate=October 20, 2013 }}</ref> Hill wrote and directed an original feature film in May, with the involvement of Death Grips in the soundtrack. During this period, Hill was also working on the group's album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/50689-death-grips-to-soundtrack-feature-film-directed-and-written-by-zach-hill-working-on-new-album/|title=Death Grips to Soundtrack Feature Film Directed and Written by Zach Hill, Working on New Album|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=May 10, 2013|work=Pitchfork|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604131743/http://pitchfork.com/news/50689-death-grips-to-soundtrack-feature-film-directed-and-written-by-zach-hill-working-on-new-album/|archivedate=June 4, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDeath Grips were scheduled to perform at [[Lollapalooza]] in August, but their performance was cancelled after the band failed to show up for an after-party show the previous night at the [[Bottom Lounge]], instead putting on a playlist of pre-recorded tracks. Draped over the back of the stage was a huge printout of a fan's suicide note, written to the band in the form of an email. Fans at the show destroyed and stole pieces of the band's equipment after being informed of the cancellation.<ref name=\"lollapalooza\">{{cite news | title = Death Grips Fans Turn Violent After Band Skips Lollapalooza After Party Appearance | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/5638123/death-grips-fans-turn-violent-after-band-skips-lollapalooza | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130805235628/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/5638123/death-grips-fans-turn-violent-after-band-skips-lollapalooza | archivedate = August 5, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Death Grips Lollapalooza Set Cancelled, Band Replaced After No-Show To Official Afterparty | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = The Huffington Post | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/03/death-grips-cancelled-lol_n_3701104.html | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130824095237/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/03/death-grips-cancelled-lol_n_3701104.html | archivedate = August 24, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Marcus | last = Gilmer | title = Death Grips bail on Lollapalooza after-show, fans destroy band's equipment | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | url = http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/band-bails-on-lollapalooza-after-show-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/ | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130807090119/http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/band-bails-on-lollapalooza-after-show-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/ | archivedate = August 7, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Miriam | last = Coleman | title = Fans Trash Death Grips' Equipment After Lollapalooza No-Show | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = Rolling Stone | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fans-trash-death-grips-equipment-after-lollapalooza-no-show-20130803 | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130805090105/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fans-trash-death-grips-equipment-after-lollapalooza-no-show-20130803 | archivedate = August 5, 2013 }}</ref> Their subsequent performance scheduled for Montreal's [[Osheaga Festival|Osheaga Music and Arts Festival]] on the next day was cancelled, as well as performances in Boston and New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/death-grips-29-1249591|title=Death Grips cancel further shows following fans trashing equipment in Chicago \u2013 NME|date=2013-08-05|work=NME|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Marc-Andr\u00e9 | last = Mongrain | title = OSHEAGA 2013 \u2013 Death Grips annule \u00e0 son tour | language = French | publisher = sorstu.ca | date = August 3, 2013 | url = http://www.sorstu.ca/osheaga-2013-death-grips-annule-a-son-tour/ | accessdate = August 4, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130806233731/http://www.sorstu.ca/osheaga-2013-death-grips-annule-a-son-tour/ | archivedate = August 6, 2013 }}</ref> The group however, never planned to actually appear at Lollapalooza; they later stated that the drum kit, suicide note, and pre-recorded music \"was the show\". The drum kit that was destroyed was revealed to be a children's learning kit and not Hill's actual kit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/51802-death-grips-never-planned-on-actually-appearing-at-their-scheduled-shows/|title=Death Grips Never Planned on Actually Appearing at Their Scheduled Shows|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225152448/http://pitchfork.com/news/51802-death-grips-never-planned-on-actually-appearing-at-their-scheduled-shows/|archivedate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Government Plates]]'' (2013) was released for free download on their official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/52999-death-grips-release-free-album-government-plates/|title=Death Grips Release Free Album Government Plates|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114012345/http://pitchfork.com/news/52999-death-grips-release-free-album-government-plates/|archivedate=14 November 2013}}</ref> An ''[[NME]]'' review called the record \"a challenging listen\" but dubbed the album along, with ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', as \"transgressive\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/death-grips/14998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813081817/http://www.nme.com/reviews/death-grips/14998|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-08-13|title=Death Grips \u2013 'Government Plates' {{!}} NME.COM|date=2016-08-13|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/death-grips-government-plates|title=Death Grips: Government Plates {{!}} Album Review {{!}} Slant Magazine|work=Slant Magazine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US}}</ref> The album \u201c[pushes] further away from typical hip-hop\" and \"[toys] with electronic dance music of various eras\", according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> In January 2014, Warp Music Publishing signed an exclusive worldwide publishing agreement with the group, covering previous and future releases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/5869815/new-signings-morrissey-signs-with-harvest-records-warp-music-publishing|title=New Signings: Morrissey Signs with Harvest Records, Warp Music Publishing Inks Death Grips, and More|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref> In June, Death Grips announced a double album titled ''[[The Powers That B]]'', along with a download of the first disc, subtitled ''Niggas on the Moon''. The second disc, ''Jenny Death'', was announced to be released later in the year.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/06/09/death-grips-drop-surprise-bjork-featuring-album-niggas-on-the-moon-download-it-now/ |title=Death Grips drop surprise, Bj\u00f6rk-featuring album niggas on the moon; download it now |publisher=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=June 8, 2014 |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714215452/http://www.factmag.com/2014/06/09/death-grips-drop-surprise-bjork-featuring-album-niggas-on-the-moon-download-it-now/ |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref> ''Niggas on the Moon'' features chopped up samples of Bj\u00f6rk's vocals.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/09/death-grips-new-album-bjork-niggas-on-the-moon|title=Death Grips land a 'thrilled' Bj\u00f6rk on their new album|last=Gibsone|first=Harriet|date=2014-06-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The double album's first half received mixed to positive reviews. ''Pitchfork'' called it the group's least intense effort in their entire discography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19472-death-grips-niggas-on-the-moon/|title=Death Grips: Niggas on the Moon Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> A review by [[MusicOMH]] stated that it had less of Hill's percussion and claimed that Morin lacked direction in producing the album.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/death-grips-powers-b|title=Death Grips \u2013 The Powers That B {{!}} Albums {{!}} musicOMH|date=2015-03-29|work=musicOMH|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> Death Grips were scheduled as a supporting act to tour with [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Soundgarden]] in July but the group announced an abrupt disbandment, thus cancelling their appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/nine_inch_nails_soundgarden_replace_death_grips_on_summer_tour_with_oneohtrix_point_never_dillinger_escape_plan_cold_cave|title=Nine Inch Nails and Soundgarden Replace Death Grips on Tour with Oneohtrix Point Never, Dillinger Escape Plan, Cold Cave|website=exclaim.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> An image of the following message, posted on their [[Facebook]] page, was written on a napkin:\n\n{{cquote|We are now at our best and so Death Grips is over. We have officially stopped. All currently scheduled live dates are canceled. Our upcoming double album ''The Powers That B'' will still be delivered worldwide later this year via Harvest/Third Worlds Records. Death Grips was and always has been a conceptual art exhibition anchored by sound and vision. Above and beyond a \"band\". To our truest fans, please stay legend.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/55781-death-grips-break-up/|title = Death Grips Break Up|date = July 2, 2014|website = Pitchfork|publisher = Pitchfork Media|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170313195233/http://pitchfork.com/news/55781-death-grips-break-up/|archivedate = March 13, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn January 2015, without any prior notification, Death Grips released a free instrumental album entitled ''[[Fashion Week (album)|Fashion Week]]''. The song titles, each beginning with the word \"Runway\" followed by a letter of the alphabet, spelled out the phrase \"JENNY DEATH WHEN\" in reference to the then-unreleased second disc of ''The Powers That B''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2015/04/review-death-grips-the-powers-that-b/|title=Review: Death Grips, 'The Powers That B'|date=2015-04-03|work=Spin|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> The album was released in its complete form in March and reached the Billboard 200 chart at No. 72.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the same year, Hill and Morin formed a side project called [[the I.L.Y's]] and issued their debut album ''[[I've Always Been Good at True Love]]'' through Death Grips' official website; it was initially released with little information about the project.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/59829-death-grips-release-album-by-mysterious-group-the-ilys/ | title=Death Grips Release Album by Mysterious Group the I.L.Y.s | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=June 4, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Gordon, Jeremy | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621211113/http://pitchfork.com/news/59829-death-grips-release-album-by-mysterious-group-the-ilys/ | archivedate=June 21, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Bottomless Pit'' and ''Year of the Snitch''===\nIn October 2015, the group uploaded a video to their YouTube page titled ''Bottomless Pit''. It features footage from 2013 of American actress [[Karen Black]] reciting lines from a film script Hill wrote months before her death. They also posted on their website and Facebook that this would be the title for [[Bottomless Pit (album)|their fifth studio album]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/death_grips_announce_bottomless_pit_album|title=Death Grips Announce 'Bottomless Pit' Album|publisher=[[Exclaim!]]|date=October 21, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023213504/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/death_grips_announce_bottomless_pit_album|archivedate=October 23, 2015}}</ref> In March, the band published a 32-minute video to their YouTube page titled ''Interview 2016'', which shares its name with [[Interview 2016|their second EP]]; the video shows the band being interviewed by Matthew Hoffman of ''Tuesdays With Matthew'', an online volunteer project that aims to combat loneliness in elderly people by recruiting them to act in recreations of famous movie scenes.<ref>http://www.matthewhoffman.tv/tuesdays-with-matthew-1</ref> However, all of the interview's audio is replaced by the album's songs, while the EP's cover art consists solely of a picture of Hoffman looking into the camera.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/03/23/death-grips-6-instrumental-tracks-ep-interview-2016/|title=Death Grips drop 6-track EP from 'Interview 2016' video|date=2016-03-23|work=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref> Death Grips uploaded their third EP, ''[[Steroids (Crouching Tiger Hidden Gabber Megamix)]]'', to their YouTube channel in May 2017; the EP consists of a single 22-minute song of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/73715-death-grips-share-new-22-minute-songmix-listen/|title=Death Grips Share New 22-Minute Song/Mix: Listen \u2013 Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525024938/http://pitchfork.com/news/73715-death-grips-share-new-22-minute-songmix-listen/|archivedate=2017-05-25}}</ref> Following this, the group co-headlined an autumn U.S. tour with [[industrial metal]] band [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-announce-tour-with-ministry/|title=Death Grips Announce Tour With Ministry \u2013 Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028200825/https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-announce-tour-with-ministry/|archivedate=2017-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/ministry-and-death-grips-are-going-on-tour-together/|title=Ministry and Death Grips Are Going On Tour Together \u2013 Consequence of Sound|website=consequenceofsound.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028144803/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/ministry-and-death-grips-are-going-on-tour-together/|archivedate=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Death Grips posted images on social media outlining that they were \"working on the new album\" titled ''[[Year of the Snitch]]'' with Australian noise artist [[Justice Yeldham|Lucas Abela]], New Zealand film director [[Andrew Adamson]], and American musician [[Justin Chancellor]] (best known as the bassist for [[Tool (band)|Tool]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-say-theyre-working-on-new-music-with-shrek-director/|title=Death Grips Working on New Music With Shrek Director {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-working-with-tools-justin-chancellor-on-new-album/|title=Death Grips Working With Tool\u2019s Justin Chancellor on New Album {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-reveal-strange-new-album-cover-art/|title=Death Grips Reveal Strange New Album Cover Art {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> In April, Death Grips uploaded a video to their YouTube channel writing the track listing for the new album with text messages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/04/11/death-grips-detail-new-album-year-of-the-snitch|title=Death Grips detail new album Year Of The Snitch|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Death Grips uploaded the singles \"Streaky\", \"Black Paint\", and \"Flies\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1996479/death-grips-black-paint/music/|title=Death Grips Share New Song \"Black Paint\"|date=2018-05-15|work=Stereogum|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> In June, they uploaded a single titled \"Hahaha\", as well as an accompanying tweet announcing the release date for ''Year of the Snitch'' as June 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/1004912306860449793|title=\u13a0eath \u13e9rips on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-06-16|language=en}}</ref> A week later, the band released another two singles: \"Dilemma\", featuring [[Andrew Adamson]], and \"Shitshow\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Death Grips|title=Death Grips \u2013 Dilemma (ft. Andrew Adamson)|date=2018-06-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3W09kTtdoBM|access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RhVN6gRD5XM</ref> On June 21, ''Year of the Snitch'' was systematically made available on streaming services after the time reached midnight on June 22 in New Zealand, subsequently leading to listeners spreading differing versions of the album hours before its full scheduled rollout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hasitleaked.com/2018/death-grips-the-year-of-the-snitch/|title=Death Grips : The Year Of The Snitch album download {{!}} Has it Leaked?|website=hasitleaked.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> The band also tweeted the album being \"leaked\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/1009869349849464832|title=\u13a0eath \u13e9rips on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref> The following day, ''Year of the Snitch'' was officially released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/06/22/death-grips-new-album-year-of-the-snitch|title=Death Grips share new album Year of the Snitch|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-06-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2019, Death Grips released a 30-minute mix titled ''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'' as part of [[Warp Records]]' 30th anniversary celebrations.\n\n==Style==\n[[File:Zach Hill.jpg|thumb|right|Ride (left) and Hill (right) performing in August 2011]]\nDeath Grips' music combines a variety of styles including [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[punk music|punk]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Tacopino |first=Joe |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/death-grips-implode-punk-and-rap-borders-on-new-lp-20120424 |title=Death Grips Implode Punk and Rap Borders on New LP |publisher=Rollingstone.com |date=2012-04-24 |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510043637/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/death-grips-implode-punk-and-rap-borders-on-new-lp-20120424 |archivedate=2015-05-10 }}</ref> [[electronic music|electronic]],<ref name=\"Utg\">{{cite web|last1=Reandelar|first1=Dana|title=Death Grips Announce North American Summer Tour|url=http://underthegunreview.net/2015/03/24/death-grips-announce-north-american-summer-tour/|website=Under the Gun|accessdate=20 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423030412/http://underthegunreview.net/2015/03/24/death-grips-announce-north-american-summer-tour/|archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> [[noise music|noise]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Chris Payne |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6509562/death-grips-north-american-tour-dates-2015-world-international-tickets |title=Death Grip Announce 2015 North American Tour Dates With International Dates Coming |publisher=Billboard |date=2015-03-24 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401085743/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6509562/death-grips-north-american-tour-dates-2015-world-international-tickets |archivedate=2016-04-01 }}</ref><ref name=SpinArtistOfTheYear>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Weingarten |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/11/death-grips-artist-year-2012-no-love-deep-web/ |title=ARTIST OF THE YEAR: DEATH GRIPS |publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=2012-11-20 |accessdate=2012-11-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128052225/https://www.spin.com/2012/11/death-grips-artist-year-2012-no-love-deep-web/ |archivedate=2012-11-28 }}</ref> and [[industrial music|industrial]]. Their style has been categorized as [[experimental hip hop]], [[rap rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/music/2013/06/10/Tonight-Death-Grips-brings-its-rap-rock-sound-to-Altar-Bar/stories/201306100137|title=Tonight: Death Grips brings its rap/rock sound to Altar Bar|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903165253/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/music/2013/06/10/Tonight-Death-Grips-brings-its-rap-rock-sound-to-Altar-Bar/stories/201306100137|archivedate=2017-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/warning-death-grips-just-announced-a-tour/|title=Warning: Death Grips just announced a tour|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903165217/https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/warning-death-grips-just-announced-a-tour/|archivedate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/ministry-death-grips-touring-together-bv-presale-for-all-dates/|title=Ministry & Death Grips touring together (BV presale for all dates)|website=BrooklynVegan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903164125/http://www.brooklynvegan.com/ministry-death-grips-touring-together-bv-presale-for-all-dates/|archivedate=2017-09-03}}</ref> [[electropunk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aux.tv/2012/05/sampled-death-grips-system-blower/|title=SAMPLED: Death Grips \u2013 &quot;System Blower&quot;|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611102724/http://www.aux.tv/2012/05/sampled-death-grips-system-blower/|archivedate=2016-06-11|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref> [[industrial hip hop]], and [[punk-rap]].<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\"/><ref name=\"gigwise-124\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/96459/death-grips-work-with-actor-robert-pattinson | title=New Death Grips Vinyl Reveals Actor Robert Pattinson Guitar Part | publisher=[[Gigwise]] | date=November 30, 2014 | accessdate=April 9, 2015 | author=Cowler, Jasmine | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414004313/http://www.gigwise.com/news/96459/death-grips-work-with-actor-robert-pattinson | archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://thequietus.com/articles/15678-death-grips-split | title=Death Grips Split | publisher=[[The Quietus]] | date=July 2, 2014 | accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9004-death-gripz/ | title=Interviews Death Grips | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=December 12, 2014 | author=Pelly, Jenn | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228201157/http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9004-death-gripz/ | archivedate=December 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"stereogum\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stereogum.com/1165062/download-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-2/mp3s/ | title=Download Death Grips NO LOVE DEEP WEB | publisher=[[Stereogum]] | date=October 1, 2012 | author=Breihan, Tom | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208082241/http://www.stereogum.com/1165062/download-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-2/mp3s/ | archivedate=December 8, 2015 }}\n</ref> The group is known for Ride's aggressive rapping style and bleak and cryptic lyrics, alongside their noisy and often chaotic production. They have also received attention for their wild physical performances and stage presence. Their live performances are notable for antics such as the destruction of instruments, their complete absence at one of their scheduled shows,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/51748-death-grips-not-playing-lollapalooza-didnt-show-up-to-their-aftershow-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/|title=Death Grips Not Playing Lollapalooza, Didn't Show Up to Their Aftershow, Fans Destroy Band's Equipment {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref> Hill drumming to the point of severe injury<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.midtownmonthly.net/music/zach-hill/ |title=Zach Hill |publisher=Midtown Monthly |date=2011-07-04 |accessdate=2018-03-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303105703/http://www.midtownmonthly.net/music/zach-hill/ |archivedate=2018-03-03 }}</ref> or performing in handcuffs,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uUVuCDEHW9k |title=Death Grips \u2013 Zach Hill Handcuffs |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-07-06 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201024737/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uUVuCDEHW9k |archivedate=2015-12-01 }}</ref> Ride's intense and chaotic stage persona, and Morin's use of live sampling alongside his improvised synthesizer flourishes and violent dancing.\n\nThey are also notable for engaging in extended periods of live musical improvisation interwoven into their set as bridges between songs, typically performed on the fly by Morin and Hill. Ride has been known to adopt many different vocal styles on record and during live performances, such as shouting, screaming, spoken word-style talking, and even whispering. Morin's unorthodox style of production and sampling and Hill's noisy, fast, and unconventional drumming styles and patterns are also distinct features of Death Grips' sound. The band is also notable for their distinctive and [[Lo-fi photography|lo-fi visual style]] made clear in their music videos, performances, and releases.\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Bj\u00f6rk]] is one of the most notable fans of the band. They remixed two tracks for ''[[Bastards (Bj\u00f6rk album)|Bastards]]'', a collection of remixes from her album ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17386-bastards/amp/|title=Bj\u00f6rk: Bastards Album Review|last=Greene|first=Jayson|date=December 11, 2012|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Bj\u00f6rk allegedly recorded original vocal samples for the band, which they used on every track of ''[[The Powers That B|Niggas on the Moon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19472-death-grips-niggas-on-the-moon/|title=Death Grips: Niggas on the Moon Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> Actor [[Robert Pattinson]] is another notable fan and collaborator of the band; he played guitar on the song \"Birds\" from ''[[Government Plates]]'',<ref name=PattinsonBirds>{{cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/57633-death-grips-birds-features-robert-pattinson-on-guitar/amp/|title=Death Grips' \"Birds\" Features Robert Pattinson on Guitar|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=November 29, 2014|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> which was achieved by Hill recording Pattinson's playing on his phone and later sampling the part into the song itself.<ref name=PattinsonBirds /> He also appeared in a 2013 photo with the band and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] backstage at the latter's concert, which received [[Viral phenomenon|viral]] attention due to its unlikely combination of people.<ref>https://www.wmagazine.com/story/robert-pattinson-beyonce-death-grips-photo/</ref> [[Kasabian]] guitarist [[Sergio Pizzorno]] cited them as an influence on the band's album ''[[48:13]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/87320/kasabian-our-new-albums-influenced-by-nirvana-+-kanye-west |title=Kasabian: 'Our new album's influenced by Nirvana + Kanye West' |publisher=Gigwise.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110045140/http://www.gigwise.com/news/87320/kasabian-our-new-albums-influenced-by-nirvana-+-kanye-west |archivedate=2015-01-10 }}</ref> According to [[David Bowie]] collaborator [[Donny McCaslin]], Bowie was inspired by Death Grips whilst creating his final album ''[[Blackstar (album)|Blackstar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/89960|title=David Bowie's new album 'Blackstar' inspired by rap group Death Grips \u2013 NME|date=26 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304110928/http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/89960|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Other notable fans include rapper [[Killer Mike]],<ref>https://twitter.com/killermike/status/631560638519767040</ref> actor [[William Shatner]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WilliamShatner|last=Shatner|first=William|number=0304110928|date=March 15, 2018|title=On and on it\u2019s beyond insane... Madness, chaos in the brain \ud83e\udde0 \ud83c\udfb6|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/william-shatner-shouts-out-death-grips/amp/|title=William Shatner Shouts Out Death Grips|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=March 15, 2018|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> rock band [[Pearl Jam]],<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cltzus2mh0E&t=1m</ref> filmmaker [[Edgar Wright]],<ref>https://twitter.com/edgarwright/status/221619943018467330</ref> rapper [[Skepta]],<ref>https://twitter.com/skepta/status/437700275349229568</ref> guitarist [[Tom Morello]],<ref>https://twitter.com/tmorello/status/633880039851868161</ref> rapper [[Danny Brown]],<ref>https://twitter.com/xdannyxbrownx/status/476163855325097985</ref> actor [[Lakeith Stanfield]],<ref>https://www.reddit.com/r/deathgrips/comments/b32kda/lakeith_stanfield_confirmed_noided/</ref> singer [[Corey Taylor]],<ref>https://www.talkhouse.com/corey-taylor-talks-death-gripss-government-plates/</ref> and musician [[Mike Shinoda]].<ref>https://www.altpress.com/news/watch_linkin_park_avenged_sevenfold_of_mice_men_members_mess_around_on_inst/</ref>\n\nThe group's song \"Hacker\" is featured in the video game ''[[Battlefield Hardline]]''. The song \"I've Seen Footage\" was used multiple times in the 2019 comedy film ''[[Booksmart]]''. Their songs have also been used on commercials and TV shows as varied as ''[[Animals.|Animals]]'', ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]'', ''[[BoJack Horseman]]'', ''[[Top Boy]]'', and ''[[Waterloo Road (TV series)|Waterloo Road]]''. The song \"No Love\" was used in ''BoJack Horseman'' during the title character's drug trips and the show included visual references to the band, such as stickers on dumpsters bearing their lyrics in the background of shots, during its final season. The song \"You Might Think He Loves You for Your Money but I Know What He Really Loves You for It's Your Brand New Leopard Skin Pillbox Hat\" was used on an [[Adidas]] Predator advertisement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oAoyxq3CwBw |title=Adidas Predator by INTERSPORT |publisher=YouTube |date=2014-07-25 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316101300/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oAoyxq3CwBw |archivedate=2016-03-16 }}</ref> The song \"Hot Head\" was used on the season 2 teaser trailer for ''Animals'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEqWkwo9Bco|title=The Animals Are Back! \u2013 Animals Season 2: Tease (HBO)|date=2017-02-10|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2017-02-11|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213173312/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEqWkwo9Bco|archivedate=2017-02-13}}</ref> as well as in the season 2 premiere of ''Atlanta'', in which the song is being played in a car by the character of aforementioned actor Lakeith Stanfield.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gavin Roberts|title=Death Grips on Atlanta!|date=2018-03-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wp6-H27J9o|accessdate=2018-03-04|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404043639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wp6-H27J9o|archivedate=2018-04-04}}</ref> The instrumental for \"Inanimate Sensation\" was used in the season 3 finale of ''Top Boy''.\n\nThe band's songs, mostly the vocals, have been featured in many [[Weird SoundCloud|SoundClown mash-ups]].<ref name=\"Noisey\">Bassil, Ryan (March 9, 2015). [https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/the-weird-nether-region-of-soundcloud-and-the-millennial-desire-to-recontextualise-content \"Welcome To Weird Soundcloud, Where the Seinfeld Theme is a Dubstep Banger\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329143236/https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/the-weird-nether-region-of-soundcloud-and-the-millennial-desire-to-recontextualise-content |date=2017-03-29 }}. ''[[Noisey]]''. Vice Media. Retrieved March 28, 2017.</ref> The band is notoriously popular on [[4chan]]'s music board /mu/, which helped \"signal-boost the group into public consciousness\".<ref name=\"Bandcamp\">Lyons, Patrick (November 11, 2019) [https://daily.bandcamp.com/2019/11/11/have-a-nice-life-sea-of-worry-interview/ \"Have a Nice Life On Their Anxiety-Driven Third Album, \u201cSea of Worry\u201d\"]. ''[[Bandcamp]]''. Retrieved November 12, 2019.</ref> On the board, the group has been referenced more than 300,000 times since 2012.\n\n==Members==\n*[[MC Ride]] \u2013 vocals and lyrics\n*[[Zach Hill]] \u2013 drums, electronic drums, and production\n*Andy Morin \u2013 production, bass guitar, audio engineering, and keyboards\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Death Grips discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'' (2012)\n*''[[No Love Deep Web]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Government Plates]]'' (2013)\n*''[[The Powers That B]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Bottomless Pit (album)|Bottomless Pit]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Year of the Snitch]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Taser | Hell Demons]]'' (2020)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n*''[[Exmilitary]]'' (2011)\n\n===Other releases===\n*''[[Death Grips (EP)|Death Grips]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Live from Death Valley]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Fashion Week (album)|Fashion Week]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Interview 2016]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Steroids (Crouching Tiger Hidden Gabber Megamix)]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Death Grips}}\n\n* {{official website|http://thirdworlds.net/}}\n\n{{Death Grips}}\n{{ConsecuenceOfSoundArtistBand}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:American experimental musical groups]]\n[[Category:American industrial music groups]]\n[[Category:Experimental hip hop]]\n[[Category:Electropunk]]\n[[Category:Hardcore punk groups from California]]\n[[Category:Electronic music groups from California]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Rap rock groups]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Harvest Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American experimental hip-hop band}}\n{{about|the hip hop band|other uses|Death grip (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Death Grips\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = File:Death grips 2014.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Death Grips in January 2014; from left to right: [[Zach Hill]], [[MC Ride]], and Andy Morin\n| origin           = [[Sacramento, California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Experimental hip hop]]\n* [[industrial hip hop]]\n* [[electropunk]]\n* [[noise music|noise]]\n* [[digital hardcore]]\n* [[rap rock]]\n* [[punk rap]]\n<!--Do not remove any genres without consulting the Talk page.-->\n}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* Third Worlds\n* [[Harvest Records|Harvest]]\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n* [[Deathbomb Arc]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hella (band)|Hella]]\n* [[The I.L.Y's]]\n* [[Bj\u00f6rk]]\n* [[Andrew Adamson]]\n* [[Justin Chancellor]]\n* [[Justice Yeldham]]\n* [[Nervous Cop]]\n* [[Tera Melos]]\n* [[Karen Black]]\n* [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]]\n* [[Nine Inch Nails]] \n* [[Les Claypool]]\n* [[Kevin Martin (British musician)|Kevin Martin]]\n}}\n| website          = {{url|thirdworlds.net}}\n| current_members  = \n* [[MC Ride]]\n* [[Zach Hill]]\n* Andy Morin\n}}\n\n'''Death Grips''' is an American [[experimental hip hop]] band formed in 2010 in [[Sacramento, California]]. The group consists of [[MC Ride]] (vocals, lyrics), [[Zach Hill]] (drums, producing), and Andy Morin (keyboards, producing).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/840695825042886656|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518235919/https://mobile.twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/840695825042886656|archivedate=2017-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|title=Suspicious Minds \u2013 The Resolute Mission Of Death Grips|work=Clash Magazine|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225328/http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Though he is not the band's frontman, Hill has been credited with being the driving creative force behind the project.<ref>https://twitter.com/andy__morin/status/908789368424296448</ref> Their sound, paired with Ride's aggressive performing style, draws on [[punk rock]], [[electronic music|electronic]], [[noise music|noise]], and [[industrial music|industrial]] styles.\n\nThe band released the mixtape ''[[Exmilitary]]'' in April 2011 and their debut studio album, ''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'', almost exactly one year later; both received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/death-grips|title=Death Grips' Scores|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105223159/http://www.metacritic.com/person/death-grips|archivedate=2012-11-05}}</ref> Shortly after signing to [[Epic Records]] in 2012, the group leaked their second album, ''[[No Love Deep Web]]'', for free download in breach of their contract and were dropped from the label. They released their third album, ''[[Government Plates]]'', in 2013. Following several broken performance commitments, the group announced their \"disbanding\" in July 2014 along with the release of their fourth album ''[[The Powers That B]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/784134414965073/?type=1&theater|title=Death Grips \u2013 Timeline Photos \u2013 Facebook|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802170305/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/784134414965073/?type=1&theater|archivedate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest |title=\u00e1\u017d eath \u00e1?\u0160rips (@bbpoltergiest) &#124; Twitter |website=Web.archive.org |date=2014-12-10 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210051214/https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest |archivedate=December 10, 2014 }}</ref> However, in March 2015, the group revealed that they \"might make some more\" music<ref name=\"facebook.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/928842713827575 |title=Death Grips \u2013 you're right, we might make some more |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227193323/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/928842713827575 |archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> and later announced a world tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/931696033542243/?type=1&theater |title=Death Grips \u2013 Timeline Photos |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804163952/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/photos/a.176170062428181.39239.170869886291532/931696033542243/?type=1&theater |archivedate=2016-08-04 }}</ref>\n\nLater in 2015, Death Grips announced their fifth official studio album, ''[[Bottomless Pit (album)|Bottomless Pit]]'', which was released in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/1043779955667183 |title=Death Grips \u2013 We've decided to make a new Death Grips... |publisher=Facebook |date=2015-10-21 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204134209/https://www.facebook.com/deathgripz/posts/1043779955667183 |archivedate=2017-02-04 }}</ref> Their sixth studio album, ''[[Year of the Snitch]]'', was released in June 2018. Their fourth EP, ''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'', was released in June 2019 in celebration of [[Warp Records]]\u2019 30th anniversary.\n\n==History==\n===2010\u20132011: Formation and ''Exmilitary''===\nDeath Grips were formed in [[Sacramento, California]], on December 21, 2010.<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> On the same day, they recorded their first song, \"Full Moon (Death Classic)\".<ref name=DeathGripsFirstInterview>{{cite web |url=http://www.deathgrips.in/interviews/the-first-interview-fucking-hater/ |title=Death Grips. The First Interview |date=2011-07-27 |accessdate=2014-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015180704/http://www.deathgrips.in/interviews/the-first-interview-fucking-hater/ |archivedate=2014-10-15 }}</ref> It was released on March 8, 2011, with a video and a [[Death Grips (EP)|free self-titled EP]] which featured the song alongside five other songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Full Moon (Death Classic) video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sFmZ6WDkuj0|accessdate=4 November 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405103122/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sFmZ6WDkuj0|archivedate=5 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Death Grips EP|publisher=[[Discogs]]|url=http://www.discogs.com/Death-Grips-Death-Grips/release/3443313|accessdate=2015-04-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150305155603/http://www.discogs.com/Death-Grips-Death-Grips/release/3443313|archivedate=2015-03-05}}</ref> On April 25, 2011, Death Grips released a free mixtape entitled ''[[Exmilitary]]'', containing three tracks from the EP along with new songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Death Grips \u2013 Exmilitary review|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|publisher=Drowned in Sound|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080412/http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Suspicious Minds \u2013 The Resolute Mission Of Death Grips|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|publisher=Clash Music|accessdate=4 November 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003035424/http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/suspicious-minds-the-resolute-mission-of-death-grips|archivedate=3 October 2012}}</ref> Throughout the spring and early summer in 2011, they played small shows while ''Exmilitary'' was spreading steadily throughout the Internet and receiving favorable reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite web|last=Patrin|first=Nate|title=Death Grips \u2013 Exmilitary \u2013 Album Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15583-exmilitary/|publisher=Pitchfork|date=2011-06-30|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127013644/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15583-exmilitary/|archivedate=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Calvert|first=John|title=Death Grip \u2013 Exmilitary Review|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|publisher=Drowned in Sound|date=2011-04-26|accessdate=2012-11-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080412/http://drownedinsound.com/releases/16426/reviews/4143291|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> The band members were largely elusive during this time, with the only confirmed member being Hill.<ref name = DeathGripsFirstInterview/>\n\n===2012: ''The Money Store'' and ''No Love Deep Web''===\n[[File:Death Grips Performing in NYC.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Death Grips performing in [[New York City]] in November 2012|right]]\nDeath Grips signed with [[Epic Records]] in February 2012, under the recommendation of Epic's then-executive vice president of marketing, [[Angelica Cob-Baehler]].<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> They announced the release of two albums in 2012. Their first studio album, ''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'', was released in April and debuted on the [[Billboard 200]] chart at No. 130.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/death-grips|title=Death Grips|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> Termed as \"avant-rap\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-money-store-mw0002325196|title=The Money Store \u2013 Death Grips {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] called ''The Money Store'' \"confrontational, abrasive, and chaotic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16512-death-grips-the-money-store/|title=Death Grips: The Money Store Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"punk rock with a hip-hop face-lift\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2012/04/album-review-death-grips-the-money-store.html|title=Album review: Death Grips' 'The Money Store'|date=2012-04-24|website=LA Times Blogs \u2013 Pop & Hiss|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOctober saw the release of ''[[No Love Deep Web]]''. It was described as a darker album by ''[[NPR]]'', saying that the group creates a \"soundtrack to modern urban living\" with lyrics that describe \"constant paranoia\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/bestmusic2012/2012/12/05/166230912/npr-musics-50-favorite-albums-of-2012|title=NPR Music's 50 Favorite Albums Of 2012|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en}}</ref> The album contains heavily edited vocal performances from Ride.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/no-love-deep-web-mw0002434684|title=No Love Deep Web \u2013 Death Grips {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> Its cover art drew attention and controversy for consisting of a picture of Hill's erect penis with the album title written across it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/48035-listen-to-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-now/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003232535/https://pitchfork.com/news/48035-listen-to-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-now/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-10-03|title=Listen to Death Grips' Album NO LOVE DEEP WEB Now, Check Out the Extremely Graphic Cover Art {{!}} News {{!}} Pitchfork|date=2012-10-03|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2012/10/album-review-death-grips-no-love-deep-web/|title=Album Review: Death Grips \u2013 NO LOVE DEEP WEB|date=2012-10-18|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/hpwx/|title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Death Grips \u2013 No Love Deep Web|last=Doran|first=John|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/01/arts/music/new-albums-throwing-muses-death-grips-the-knells-psapp.html|title=New Albums: Throwing Muses, Death Grips, the Knells, Psapp|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=2013-11-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The album was recorded within four months in Sacramento.<ref name = SpinArtistOfTheYear/> Prior to that, an international tour was scheduled to support ''The Money Store'', but was immediately cancelled in order to complete ''No Love Deep Web.'' This caused conflict between the group and their fans, as well as their label Epic Records.<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\" /> In particular, the album was self-released for legal download via [[BitTorrent]] as an effort to bypass their label's original intent to release the album in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083590/death-grips-top-bittorrents-list-of-most-legally-downloaded-music|title=Death Grips Top BitTorrent's List of Most Legally Downloaded Music|author=Van Buskirk, Eliot|date=October 1, 2012|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813203441/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1083590/death-grips-top-bittorrents-list-of-most-legally-downloaded-music|archivedate=August 13, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/06/public-enemy-bittorrent-bundle-chuck-d-death-grips-p2p-free-download/|title=Public Enemy and Death Grips Use New BitTorrent Bundle to Connect With Fans|author=Raymond, Adam K.|date=June 21, 2013|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827034120/https://www.spin.com/2013/06/public-enemy-bittorrent-bundle-chuck-d-death-grips-p2p-free-download/|archivedate=August 27, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/death-grips/66397|title=Death Grips defy their label with free album release \u2013 listen|date=October 1, 2012|publisher=[[NME]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613051119/http://www.nme.com/news/death-grips/66397|archivedate=June 13, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> Death Grips was cut from their recording contract as a result,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474346/death-grips-dropped-by-epic-following-album-leak|title=Death Grips Dropped By Epic Records Following Album Leak|last=Stutz|first=Colin|date=2012-11-02|work=Billboard|accessdate=2012-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220125625/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474346/death-grips-dropped-by-epic-following-album-leak|archivedate=2016-12-20|url-status=live|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc}}</ref> and would launch their new label Third Worlds in the following year from \"a unique relationship with [[Harvest Records|Harvest]]/[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\u201d. Material would then be distributed by [[Caroline Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/51428-death-grips-launch-new-label-thirdworlds-for-new-album-out-in-2014/|title=Death Grips Launch New Label Third Worlds|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=July 8, 2013|work=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710150543/http://pitchfork.com/news/51428-death-grips-launch-new-label-thirdworlds-for-new-album-out-in-2014/|archivedate=July 10, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe band remixed two [[Bj\u00f6rk]] songs from her album [[Biophilia (album)|''Biophilia'']], \"Sacrifice\" and \"Thunderbolt\", after receiving an artist-to-artist note of support.<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\" /> The re-workings were featured in her 2012 remix album ''[[Bastards (Bj\u00f6rk album)|Bastards]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/z4nv/|title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Bj\u00f6rk \u2013 Bastards|last=Diver|first=Mike|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> A non-album track titled \"True Vulture Bare\" was issued in October 2012 and was accompanied with an animated video by Galen Pehrson. This project was created for the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/48248-new-death-grips-trackvideo-true-vulture/|title=New Death Grips Track/Video: \"True Vulture\" {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132015: ''Government Plates'' and ''The Powers That B''===\n[[File:Death Grips 2013.jpg|thumb|240px|Death Grips performing in [[Moscow]] in May 2013|left]]\nIn March 2013, the band released a series of videos to their [[YouTube]] account, collectively called ''No Hands''. On March 20, 2013, a music video for \"Lock Your Doors\", which was recorded at a live show in [[SXSW]], was released.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/50035-watch-death-grips-share-disorienting-lock-your-doors-video-explain-no-hands-series/ | title=Watch: Death Grips Share Disorienting \"Lock Your Doors\" Video, Explain \"No Hands\" Series | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=March 20, 2013 | accessdate=August 22, 2013 | author=Battan, Carrie | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323002533/http://pitchfork.com/news/50035-watch-death-grips-share-disorienting-lock-your-doors-video-explain-no-hands-series/ | archivedate=March 23, 2013 }}</ref> Hill did not attend the show physically, but played the drums via [[Skype]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spin.com/2013/03/death-grips-lock-your-doors-no-hands-video-sxsw/ | title=See Death Grips' Disorienting Head-Cam and Skype-Shot 'Lock Your Doors' | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=March 20, 2013 | accessdate=August 22, 2013 | author=Marthins, Chris | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020140831/https://www.spin.com/2013/03/death-grips-lock-your-doors-no-hands-video-sxsw/ | archivedate=October 20, 2013 }}</ref> Hill wrote and directed an original feature film in May, with the involvement of Death Grips in the soundtrack. During this period, Hill was also working on the group's album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/50689-death-grips-to-soundtrack-feature-film-directed-and-written-by-zach-hill-working-on-new-album/|title=Death Grips to Soundtrack Feature Film Directed and Written by Zach Hill, Working on New Album|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=May 10, 2013|work=Pitchfork|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604131743/http://pitchfork.com/news/50689-death-grips-to-soundtrack-feature-film-directed-and-written-by-zach-hill-working-on-new-album/|archivedate=June 4, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDeath Grips were scheduled to perform at [[Lollapalooza]] in August, but their performance was cancelled after the band failed to show up for an after-party show the previous night at the [[Bottom Lounge]], instead putting on a playlist of pre-recorded tracks. Draped over the back of the stage was a huge printout of a fan's suicide note, written to the band in the form of an email. Fans at the show destroyed and stole pieces of the band's equipment after being informed of the cancellation.<ref name=\"lollapalooza\">{{cite news | title = Death Grips Fans Turn Violent After Band Skips Lollapalooza After Party Appearance | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/5638123/death-grips-fans-turn-violent-after-band-skips-lollapalooza | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130805235628/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/5638123/death-grips-fans-turn-violent-after-band-skips-lollapalooza | archivedate = August 5, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Death Grips Lollapalooza Set Cancelled, Band Replaced After No-Show To Official Afterparty | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = The Huffington Post | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/03/death-grips-cancelled-lol_n_3701104.html | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130824095237/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/03/death-grips-cancelled-lol_n_3701104.html | archivedate = August 24, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Marcus | last = Gilmer | title = Death Grips bail on Lollapalooza after-show, fans destroy band's equipment | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | url = http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/band-bails-on-lollapalooza-after-show-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/ | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130807090119/http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/band-bails-on-lollapalooza-after-show-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/ | archivedate = August 7, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Miriam | last = Coleman | title = Fans Trash Death Grips' Equipment After Lollapalooza No-Show | date = August 3, 2013 | publisher = Rolling Stone | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fans-trash-death-grips-equipment-after-lollapalooza-no-show-20130803 | accessdate = August 3, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130805090105/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/fans-trash-death-grips-equipment-after-lollapalooza-no-show-20130803 | archivedate = August 5, 2013 }}</ref> Their subsequent performance scheduled for Montreal's [[Osheaga Festival|Osheaga Music and Arts Festival]] on the next day was cancelled, as well as performances in Boston and New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/death-grips-29-1249591|title=Death Grips cancel further shows following fans trashing equipment in Chicago \u2013 NME|date=2013-08-05|work=NME|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Marc-Andr\u00e9 | last = Mongrain | title = OSHEAGA 2013 \u2013 Death Grips annule \u00e0 son tour | language = French | publisher = sorstu.ca | date = August 3, 2013 | url = http://www.sorstu.ca/osheaga-2013-death-grips-annule-a-son-tour/ | accessdate = August 4, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130806233731/http://www.sorstu.ca/osheaga-2013-death-grips-annule-a-son-tour/ | archivedate = August 6, 2013 }}</ref> The group however, never planned to actually appear at Lollapalooza; they later stated that the drum kit, suicide note, and pre-recorded music \"was the show\". The drum kit that was destroyed was revealed to be a children's learning kit and not Hill's actual kit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/51802-death-grips-never-planned-on-actually-appearing-at-their-scheduled-shows/|title=Death Grips Never Planned on Actually Appearing at Their Scheduled Shows|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225152448/http://pitchfork.com/news/51802-death-grips-never-planned-on-actually-appearing-at-their-scheduled-shows/|archivedate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Government Plates]]'' (2013) was released for free download on their official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/52999-death-grips-release-free-album-government-plates/|title=Death Grips Release Free Album Government Plates|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=5 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114012345/http://pitchfork.com/news/52999-death-grips-release-free-album-government-plates/|archivedate=14 November 2013}}</ref> An ''[[NME]]'' review called the record \"a challenging listen\" but dubbed the album along, with ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', as \"transgressive\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/death-grips/14998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813081817/http://www.nme.com/reviews/death-grips/14998|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-08-13|title=Death Grips \u2013 'Government Plates' {{!}} NME.COM|date=2016-08-13|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/death-grips-government-plates|title=Death Grips: Government Plates {{!}} Album Review {{!}} Slant Magazine|work=Slant Magazine|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US}}</ref> The album \u201c[pushes] further away from typical hip-hop\" and \"[toys] with electronic dance music of various eras\", according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> In January 2014, Warp Music Publishing signed an exclusive worldwide publishing agreement with the group, covering previous and future releases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/5869815/new-signings-morrissey-signs-with-harvest-records-warp-music-publishing|title=New Signings: Morrissey Signs with Harvest Records, Warp Music Publishing Inks Death Grips, and More|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref> In June, Death Grips announced a double album titled ''[[The Powers That B]]'', along with a download of the first disc, subtitled ''Niggas on the Moon''. The second disc, ''Jenny Death'', was announced to be released later in the year.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/06/09/death-grips-drop-surprise-bjork-featuring-album-niggas-on-the-moon-download-it-now/ |title=Death Grips drop surprise, Bj\u00f6rk-featuring album niggas on the moon; download it now |publisher=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |date=June 8, 2014 |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714215452/http://www.factmag.com/2014/06/09/death-grips-drop-surprise-bjork-featuring-album-niggas-on-the-moon-download-it-now/ |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref> ''Niggas on the Moon'' features chopped up samples of Bj\u00f6rk's vocals.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/09/death-grips-new-album-bjork-niggas-on-the-moon|title=Death Grips land a 'thrilled' Bj\u00f6rk on their new album|last=Gibsone|first=Harriet|date=2014-06-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The double album's first half received mixed to positive reviews. ''Pitchfork'' called it the group's least intense effort in their entire discography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19472-death-grips-niggas-on-the-moon/|title=Death Grips: Niggas on the Moon Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> A review by [[MusicOMH]] stated that it had less of Hill's percussion and claimed that Morin lacked direction in producing the album.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/death-grips-powers-b|title=Death Grips \u2013 The Powers That B {{!}} Albums {{!}} musicOMH|date=2015-03-29|work=musicOMH|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> Death Grips were scheduled as a supporting act to tour with [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Soundgarden]] in July but the group announced an abrupt disbandment, thus cancelling their appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/nine_inch_nails_soundgarden_replace_death_grips_on_summer_tour_with_oneohtrix_point_never_dillinger_escape_plan_cold_cave|title=Nine Inch Nails and Soundgarden Replace Death Grips on Tour with Oneohtrix Point Never, Dillinger Escape Plan, Cold Cave|website=exclaim.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> An image of the following message, posted on their [[Facebook]] page, was written on a napkin:\n\n{{cquote|We are now at our best and so Death Grips is over. We have officially stopped. All currently scheduled live dates are canceled. Our upcoming double album ''The Powers That B'' will still be delivered worldwide later this year via Harvest/Third Worlds Records. Death Grips was and always has been a conceptual art exhibition anchored by sound and vision. Above and beyond a \"band\". To our truest fans, please stay legend.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://pitchfork.com/news/55781-death-grips-break-up/|title = Death Grips Break Up|date = July 2, 2014|website = Pitchfork|publisher = Pitchfork Media|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170313195233/http://pitchfork.com/news/55781-death-grips-break-up/|archivedate = March 13, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn January 2015, without any prior notification, Death Grips released a free instrumental album entitled ''[[Fashion Week (album)|Fashion Week]]''. The song titles, each beginning with the word \"Runway\" followed by a letter of the alphabet, spelled out the phrase \"JENNY DEATH WHEN\" in reference to the then-unreleased second disc of ''The Powers That B''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spin.com/2015/04/review-death-grips-the-powers-that-b/|title=Review: Death Grips, 'The Powers That B'|date=2015-04-03|work=Spin|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> The album was released in its complete form in March and reached the Billboard 200 chart at No. 72.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the same year, Hill and Morin formed a side project called [[the I.L.Y's]] and issued their debut album ''[[I've Always Been Good at True Love]]'' through Death Grips' official website; it was initially released with little information about the project.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/59829-death-grips-release-album-by-mysterious-group-the-ilys/ | title=Death Grips Release Album by Mysterious Group the I.L.Y.s | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=June 4, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Gordon, Jeremy | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621211113/http://pitchfork.com/news/59829-death-grips-release-album-by-mysterious-group-the-ilys/ | archivedate=June 21, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''Bottomless Pit'' and ''Year of the Snitch''===\nIn October 2015, the group uploaded a video to their YouTube page titled ''Bottomless Pit''. It features footage from 2013 of American actress [[Karen Black]] reciting lines from a film script Hill wrote months before her death. They also posted on their website and Facebook that this would be the title for [[Bottomless Pit (album)|their fifth studio album]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/death_grips_announce_bottomless_pit_album|title=Death Grips Announce 'Bottomless Pit' Album|publisher=[[Exclaim!]]|date=October 21, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023213504/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/death_grips_announce_bottomless_pit_album|archivedate=October 23, 2015}}</ref> In March, the band published a 32-minute video to their YouTube page titled ''Interview 2016'', which shares its name with [[Interview 2016|their second EP]]; the video shows the band being interviewed by Matthew Hoffman of ''Tuesdays With Matthew'', an online volunteer project that aims to combat loneliness in elderly people by recruiting them to act in recreations of famous movie scenes.<ref>http://www.matthewhoffman.tv/tuesdays-with-matthew-1</ref> However, all of the interview's audio is replaced by the album's songs, while the EP's cover art consists solely of a picture of Hoffman looking into the camera.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/03/23/death-grips-6-instrumental-tracks-ep-interview-2016/|title=Death Grips drop 6-track EP from 'Interview 2016' video|date=2016-03-23|work=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref> Death Grips uploaded their third EP, ''[[Steroids (Crouching Tiger Hidden Gabber Megamix)]]'', to their YouTube channel in May 2017; the EP consists of a single 22-minute song of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/73715-death-grips-share-new-22-minute-songmix-listen/|title=Death Grips Share New 22-Minute Song/Mix: Listen \u2013 Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525024938/http://pitchfork.com/news/73715-death-grips-share-new-22-minute-songmix-listen/|archivedate=2017-05-25}}</ref> Following this, the group co-headlined an autumn U.S. tour with [[industrial metal]] band [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-announce-tour-with-ministry/|title=Death Grips Announce Tour With Ministry \u2013 Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028200825/https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-announce-tour-with-ministry/|archivedate=2017-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/ministry-and-death-grips-are-going-on-tour-together/|title=Ministry and Death Grips Are Going On Tour Together \u2013 Consequence of Sound|website=consequenceofsound.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028144803/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/ministry-and-death-grips-are-going-on-tour-together/|archivedate=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Death Grips posted images on social media outlining that they were \"working on the new album\" titled ''[[Year of the Snitch]]'' with Australian noise artist [[Justice Yeldham|Lucas Abela]], New Zealand film director [[Andrew Adamson]], and American musician [[Justin Chancellor]] (best known as the bassist for [[Tool (band)|Tool]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-say-theyre-working-on-new-music-with-shrek-director/|title=Death Grips Working on New Music With Shrek Director {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-working-with-tools-justin-chancellor-on-new-album/|title=Death Grips Working With Tool\u2019s Justin Chancellor on New Album {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/death-grips-reveal-strange-new-album-cover-art/|title=Death Grips Reveal Strange New Album Cover Art {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> In April, Death Grips uploaded a video to their YouTube channel writing the track listing for the new album with text messages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/04/11/death-grips-detail-new-album-year-of-the-snitch|title=Death Grips detail new album Year Of The Snitch|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-04-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Death Grips uploaded the singles \"Streaky\", \"Black Paint\", and \"Flies\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1996479/death-grips-black-paint/music/|title=Death Grips Share New Song \"Black Paint\"|date=2018-05-15|work=Stereogum|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> In June, they uploaded a single titled \"Hahaha\", as well as an accompanying tweet announcing the release date for ''Year of the Snitch'' as June 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/1004912306860449793|title=\u13a0eath \u13e9rips on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-06-16|language=en}}</ref> A week later, the band released another two singles: \"Dilemma\", featuring [[Andrew Adamson]], and \"Shitshow\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Death Grips|title=Death Grips \u2013 Dilemma (ft. Andrew Adamson)|date=2018-06-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3W09kTtdoBM|access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RhVN6gRD5XM</ref> On June 21, ''Year of the Snitch'' was systematically made available on streaming services after the time reached midnight on June 22 in New Zealand, subsequently leading to listeners spreading differing versions of the album hours before its full scheduled rollout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hasitleaked.com/2018/death-grips-the-year-of-the-snitch/|title=Death Grips : The Year Of The Snitch album download {{!}} Has it Leaked?|website=hasitleaked.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> The band also tweeted the album being \"leaked\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/bbpoltergiest/status/1009869349849464832|title=\u13a0eath \u13e9rips on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref> The following day, ''Year of the Snitch'' was officially released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/06/22/death-grips-new-album-year-of-the-snitch|title=Death Grips share new album Year of the Snitch|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-06-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2019, Death Grips released a 30-minute mix titled ''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'' as part of [[Warp Records]]' 30th anniversary celebrations.\n\n==Style==\n[[File:Zach Hill.jpg|thumb|right|Ride (left) and Hill (right) performing in August 2011]]\nDeath Grips' music combines a variety of styles including [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[punk music|punk]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Tacopino |first=Joe |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/death-grips-implode-punk-and-rap-borders-on-new-lp-20120424 |title=Death Grips Implode Punk and Rap Borders on New LP |publisher=Rollingstone.com |date=2012-04-24 |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510043637/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/death-grips-implode-punk-and-rap-borders-on-new-lp-20120424 |archivedate=2015-05-10 }}</ref> [[electronic music|electronic]],<ref name=\"Utg\">{{cite web|last1=Reandelar|first1=Dana|title=Death Grips Announce North American Summer Tour|url=http://underthegunreview.net/2015/03/24/death-grips-announce-north-american-summer-tour/|website=Under the Gun|accessdate=20 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423030412/http://underthegunreview.net/2015/03/24/death-grips-announce-north-american-summer-tour/|archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> [[noise music|noise]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Chris Payne |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6509562/death-grips-north-american-tour-dates-2015-world-international-tickets |title=Death Grip Announce 2015 North American Tour Dates With International Dates Coming |publisher=Billboard |date=2015-03-24 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401085743/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6509562/death-grips-north-american-tour-dates-2015-world-international-tickets |archivedate=2016-04-01 }}</ref><ref name=SpinArtistOfTheYear>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Weingarten |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/11/death-grips-artist-year-2012-no-love-deep-web/ |title=ARTIST OF THE YEAR: DEATH GRIPS |publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=2012-11-20 |accessdate=2012-11-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128052225/https://www.spin.com/2012/11/death-grips-artist-year-2012-no-love-deep-web/ |archivedate=2012-11-28 }}</ref> and [[industrial music|industrial]]. Their style has been categorized as [[experimental hip hop]], [[rap rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/music/2013/06/10/Tonight-Death-Grips-brings-its-rap-rock-sound-to-Altar-Bar/stories/201306100137|title=Tonight: Death Grips brings its rap/rock sound to Altar Bar|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903165253/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/music/2013/06/10/Tonight-Death-Grips-brings-its-rap-rock-sound-to-Altar-Bar/stories/201306100137|archivedate=2017-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/warning-death-grips-just-announced-a-tour/|title=Warning: Death Grips just announced a tour|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903165217/https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/warning-death-grips-just-announced-a-tour/|archivedate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/ministry-death-grips-touring-together-bv-presale-for-all-dates/|title=Ministry & Death Grips touring together (BV presale for all dates)|website=BrooklynVegan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903164125/http://www.brooklynvegan.com/ministry-death-grips-touring-together-bv-presale-for-all-dates/|archivedate=2017-09-03}}</ref> [[electropunk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aux.tv/2012/05/sampled-death-grips-system-blower/|title=SAMPLED: Death Grips \u2013 &quot;System Blower&quot;|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611102724/http://www.aux.tv/2012/05/sampled-death-grips-system-blower/|archivedate=2016-06-11|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref> [[industrial hip hop]], and [[punk-rap]].<ref name=\"SpinArtistOfTheYear\"/><ref name=\"gigwise-124\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/96459/death-grips-work-with-actor-robert-pattinson | title=New Death Grips Vinyl Reveals Actor Robert Pattinson Guitar Part | publisher=[[Gigwise]] | date=November 30, 2014 | accessdate=April 9, 2015 | author=Cowler, Jasmine | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414004313/http://www.gigwise.com/news/96459/death-grips-work-with-actor-robert-pattinson | archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://thequietus.com/articles/15678-death-grips-split | title=Death Grips Split | publisher=[[The Quietus]] | date=July 2, 2014 | accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9004-death-gripz/ | title=Interviews Death Grips | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=December 12, 2014 | author=Pelly, Jenn | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228201157/http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/9004-death-gripz/ | archivedate=December 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"stereogum\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stereogum.com/1165062/download-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-2/mp3s/ | title=Download Death Grips NO LOVE DEEP WEB | publisher=[[Stereogum]] | date=October 1, 2012 | author=Breihan, Tom | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208082241/http://www.stereogum.com/1165062/download-death-grips-no-love-deep-web-2/mp3s/ | archivedate=December 8, 2015 }}\n</ref> The group is known for Ride's aggressive rapping style and bleak and cryptic lyrics, alongside their noisy and often chaotic production. They have also received attention for their wild physical performances and stage presence. Their live performances are notable for antics such as the destruction of instruments, their complete absence at one of their scheduled shows,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/51748-death-grips-not-playing-lollapalooza-didnt-show-up-to-their-aftershow-fans-destroy-bands-equipment/|title=Death Grips Not Playing Lollapalooza, Didn't Show Up to Their Aftershow, Fans Destroy Band's Equipment {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref> Hill drumming to the point of severe injury<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.midtownmonthly.net/music/zach-hill/ |title=Zach Hill |publisher=Midtown Monthly |date=2011-07-04 |accessdate=2018-03-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303105703/http://www.midtownmonthly.net/music/zach-hill/ |archivedate=2018-03-03 }}</ref> or performing in handcuffs,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uUVuCDEHW9k |title=Death Grips \u2013 Zach Hill Handcuffs |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-07-06 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201024737/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uUVuCDEHW9k |archivedate=2015-12-01 }}</ref> Ride's intense and chaotic stage persona, and Morin's use of live sampling alongside his improvised synthesizer flourishes and violent dancing.\n\nThey are also notable for engaging in extended periods of live musical improvisation interwoven into their set as bridges between songs, typically performed on the fly by Morin and Hill. Ride has been known to adopt many different vocal styles on record and during live performances, such as shouting, screaming, spoken word-style talking, and even whispering. Morin's unorthodox style of production and sampling and Hill's noisy, fast, and unconventional drumming styles and patterns are also distinct features of Death Grips' sound. The band is also notable for their distinctive and [[Lo-fi photography|lo-fi visual style]] made clear in their music videos, performances, and releases.\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Bj\u00f6rk]] is one of the most notable fans of the band. They remixed two tracks for ''[[Bastards (Bj\u00f6rk album)|Bastards]]'', a collection of remixes from her album ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17386-bastards/amp/|title=Bj\u00f6rk: Bastards Album Review|last=Greene|first=Jayson|date=December 11, 2012|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Bj\u00f6rk allegedly recorded original vocal samples for the band, which they used on every track of ''[[The Powers That B|Niggas on the Moon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19472-death-grips-niggas-on-the-moon/|title=Death Grips: Niggas on the Moon Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> Actor [[Robert Pattinson]] is another notable fan and collaborator of the band; he played guitar on the song \"Birds\" from ''[[Government Plates]]'',<ref name=PattinsonBirds>{{cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/57633-death-grips-birds-features-robert-pattinson-on-guitar/amp/|title=Death Grips' \"Birds\" Features Robert Pattinson on Guitar|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=November 29, 2014|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> which was achieved by Hill recording Pattinson's playing on his phone and later sampling the part into the song itself.<ref name=PattinsonBirds /> He also appeared in a 2013 photo with the band and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] backstage at the latter's concert, which received [[Viral phenomenon|viral]] attention due to its unlikely combination of people.<ref>https://www.wmagazine.com/story/robert-pattinson-beyonce-death-grips-photo/</ref> [[Kasabian]] guitarist [[Sergio Pizzorno]] cited them as an influence on the band's album ''[[48:13]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/87320/kasabian-our-new-albums-influenced-by-nirvana-+-kanye-west |title=Kasabian: 'Our new album's influenced by Nirvana + Kanye West' |publisher=Gigwise.com |accessdate=2015-04-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110045140/http://www.gigwise.com/news/87320/kasabian-our-new-albums-influenced-by-nirvana-+-kanye-west |archivedate=2015-01-10 }}</ref> According to [[David Bowie]] collaborator [[Donny McCaslin]], Bowie was inspired by Death Grips whilst creating his final album ''[[Blackstar (album)|Blackstar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/89960|title=David Bowie's new album 'Blackstar' inspired by rap group Death Grips \u2013 NME|date=26 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304110928/http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/89960|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Other notable fans include rapper [[Killer Mike]],<ref>https://twitter.com/killermike/status/631560638519767040</ref> actor [[William Shatner]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WilliamShatner|last=Shatner|first=William|number=0304110928|date=March 15, 2018|title=On and on it\u2019s beyond insane... Madness, chaos in the brain \ud83e\udde0 \ud83c\udfb6|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/william-shatner-shouts-out-death-grips/amp/|title=William Shatner Shouts Out Death Grips|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=March 15, 2018|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> rock band [[Pearl Jam]],<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cltzus2mh0E&t=1m</ref> filmmaker [[Edgar Wright]],<ref>https://twitter.com/edgarwright/status/221619943018467330</ref> rapper [[Skepta]],<ref>https://twitter.com/skepta/status/437700275349229568</ref> guitarist [[Tom Morello]],<ref>https://twitter.com/tmorello/status/633880039851868161</ref> rapper [[Danny Brown]],<ref>https://twitter.com/xdannyxbrownx/status/476163855325097985</ref> actor [[Lakeith Stanfield]],<ref>https://www.reddit.com/r/deathgrips/comments/b32kda/lakeith_stanfield_confirmed_noided/</ref> singer [[Corey Taylor]],<ref>https://www.talkhouse.com/corey-taylor-talks-death-gripss-government-plates/</ref> and musician [[Mike Shinoda]].<ref>https://www.altpress.com/news/watch_linkin_park_avenged_sevenfold_of_mice_men_members_mess_around_on_inst/</ref>\n\nThe group's song \"Hacker\" is featured in the video game ''[[Battlefield Hardline]]''. The song \"I've Seen Footage\" was used multiple times in the 2019 comedy film ''[[Booksmart]]''. Their songs have also been used on commercials and TV shows as varied as ''[[Animals.|Animals]]'', ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]'', ''[[BoJack Horseman]]'', ''[[Top Boy]]'', and ''[[Waterloo Road (TV series)|Waterloo Road]]''. The song \"No Love\" was used in ''BoJack Horseman'' during the title character's drug trips and the show included visual references to the band, such as stickers on dumpsters bearing their lyrics in the background of shots, during its final season. The song \"You Might Think He Loves You for Your Money but I Know What He Really Loves You for It's Your Brand New Leopard Skin Pillbox Hat\" was used on an [[Adidas]] Predator advertisement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oAoyxq3CwBw |title=Adidas Predator by INTERSPORT |publisher=YouTube |date=2014-07-25 |accessdate=2016-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316101300/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oAoyxq3CwBw |archivedate=2016-03-16 }}</ref> The song \"Hot Head\" was used on the season 2 teaser trailer for ''Animals'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEqWkwo9Bco|title=The Animals Are Back! \u2013 Animals Season 2: Tease (HBO)|date=2017-02-10|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2017-02-11|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213173312/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEqWkwo9Bco|archivedate=2017-02-13}}</ref> as well as in the season 2 premiere of ''Atlanta'', in which the song is being played in a car by the character of aforementioned actor Lakeith Stanfield.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gavin Roberts|title=Death Grips on Atlanta!|date=2018-03-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wp6-H27J9o|accessdate=2018-03-04|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404043639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wp6-H27J9o|archivedate=2018-04-04}}</ref> The instrumental for \"Inanimate Sensation\" was used in the season 3 finale of ''Top Boy''.\n\nThe band's songs, mostly the vocals, have been featured in many [[Weird SoundCloud|SoundClown mash-ups]].<ref name=\"Noisey\">Bassil, Ryan (March 9, 2015). [https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/the-weird-nether-region-of-soundcloud-and-the-millennial-desire-to-recontextualise-content \"Welcome To Weird Soundcloud, Where the Seinfeld Theme is a Dubstep Banger\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329143236/https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/the-weird-nether-region-of-soundcloud-and-the-millennial-desire-to-recontextualise-content |date=2017-03-29 }}. ''[[Noisey]]''. Vice Media. Retrieved March 28, 2017.</ref> The band is notoriously popular on [[4chan]]'s music board /mu/, which helped \"signal-boost the group into public consciousness\".<ref name=\"Bandcamp\">Lyons, Patrick (November 11, 2019) [https://daily.bandcamp.com/2019/11/11/have-a-nice-life-sea-of-worry-interview/ \"Have a Nice Life On Their Anxiety-Driven Third Album, \u201cSea of Worry\u201d\"]. ''[[Bandcamp]]''. Retrieved November 12, 2019.</ref> On the board, the group has been referenced more than 300,000 times since 2012.\n\n==Members==\n*[[MC Ride]] \u2013 vocals and lyrics\n*[[Zach Hill]] \u2013 drums, electronic drums, and production\n*Andy Morin \u2013 production, bass guitar, audio engineering, and keyboards\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Death Grips discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[The Money Store (album)|The Money Store]]'' (2012)\n*''[[No Love Deep Web]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Government Plates]]'' (2013)\n*''[[The Powers That B]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Bottomless Pit (album)|Bottomless Pit]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Year of the Snitch]]'' (2018)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n*''[[Exmilitary]]'' (2011)\n\n===Other releases===\n*''[[Death Grips (EP)|Death Grips]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Live from Death Valley]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Fashion Week (album)|Fashion Week]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Interview 2016]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Steroids (Crouching Tiger Hidden Gabber Megamix)]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Gmail and the Restraining Orders]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Death Grips}}\n\n* {{official website|http://thirdworlds.net/}}\n\n{{Death Grips}}\n{{ConsecuenceOfSoundArtistBand}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:American experimental musical groups]]\n[[Category:American industrial music groups]]\n[[Category:Experimental hip hop]]\n[[Category:Electropunk]]\n[[Category:Hardcore punk groups from California]]\n[[Category:Electronic music groups from California]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Rap rock groups]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Harvest Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Jfushsbanaisjwnwn", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_Grips"}
{"title_page": "Theudebert II", "text_new": "[[File:Tiers_de_sou_de_Th%C3%A9odebert_II_frapp%C3%A9_%C3%A0_Clermont.png|thumb|A ''[[tremissis]]'' of Theudebert II minted at Clermont]]\n'''Theudebert II''' ({{Lang-fr|Thibert ou Th\u00e9odebert}}) (c.585-612),{{sfn|Murray|2018|p=1494}} King of [[Austrasia]] (595\u2013612 [[AD]]), was the son and heir of [[Childebert II]]. He received the kingdom of Austrasia plus the cities (''civitates'') of [[Poitiers]], [[Tours]], [[Le Puy-en-Velay]], [[Bordeaux]], and [[Ch\u00e2teaudun]], as well as the [[Champagne (historical province)|Champagne]], the [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne]], and [[Alamannia|Transjurane Alemannia]].\n\nDuring his early years, his grandmother [[Brunhilda of Austrasia|Brunhilda]] ruled for Theudebert and his brother [[Theuderic II]], who had received the realm of Burgundy. After the two brothers reached adulthood, they were often at war, with Brunhilda siding with Theuderic. In 599, Theuderic defeated Theudebert at [[Sens]], but then the two brothers allied against their cousin [[Chlothar II]] and defeated him at [[Dormelles]] (near [[Montereau-Fault-Yonne|Montereau]]), thereby laying their hands on a great portion of [[Neustria]] (600&ndash;604). At this point, however, the two brothers took up arms against each other; Theuderic defeated Theudebert at [[\u00c9tampes]] and he refused to aid his brother when Theuderic's kingdom was invaded by Clothar II in 605. In 610, he{{who|date=April 2020}} extorted [[Alsace]] from his brother and Theuderic took up arms against him, yet again.\n\nTheudebert was defeated handily by Theuderic at [[Toul]] and at [[Z\u00fclpich]] in 612.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=A09WDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1494&lpg=PA1494&dq=Theudebert+II&source=bl&ots=8viJoJdIou&sig=BxleQHcc-Cljo79zPwcTrsIR-7c&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiwsrmay7rbAhUEvFkKHRKzCiw4FBDoAQg1MAI#v=onepage&q=Theudebert%20II&f=false McCollum, Adam Carter. \"Theudebert II\", ''The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity'', (Oliver Nicholson, ed.), Oxford University Press, 2018], {{ISBN|9780192562463}}</ref><ref>Laury Sarti, ''Perceiving War and the Military in Early Christian Gaul (ca. 400\u2013700 A.D.)'', [[Brill Publishers]], Leiden, 2013, {{ISBN|9789004258051}}, {{p.|89}}</ref><ref>[[Jeffrey Burton Russell]], ''Medieval Civilization'' Wipf and Stock Publishers, 2005, p.145</ref> Theudebert was locked up in a monastery at the order of his grandmother, and assassinated with his son Merovech.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PDkNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA522&lpg=PA522&dq=chlothar+ii+king+of+the+franks&source=bl&ots=SfxGkR8c1B&sig=ACfU3U2vrWdR16hbvtNfzk15wtURHXOzlg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf46bfu7rkAhUjUt8KHRzLD0Y4KBDoATADegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q&f=false Oman, Charles. ''The Dark Ages, 476-918'', Rivingtons, 1908, p. 173]{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nHe was married to [[Bilichildis]]. His daughter [[Emma of Austrasia|Emma]] is sometimes thought to have married [[Eadbald of Kent]].\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Brunhilda|volume=4|page=684}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite dictionary |title=Theudebert II |first=Alexander C. |last=Murray |dictionary=The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity |volume=Vol. I |editor-first=Oliver |editor-last=Nicholson |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2018 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Merovingian|Merovingian dynasty]]||586||612}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Childebert II]]| title=[[List of Frankish kings|King of Austrasia]] | years=595&ndash;612 | after=[[Theuderic II]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Theudebert Ii}}\n[[Category:Merovingian kings]]\n[[Category:Frankish warriors]]\n[[Category:586 births]]\n[[Category:612 deaths]]\n[[Category:Medieval child rulers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Frankish kings]]\n[[Category:Murdered royalty]]\n[[Category:7th-century Frankish kings]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Tiers_de_sou_de_Th%C3%A9odebert_II_frapp%C3%A9_%C3%A0_Clermont.png|thumb|A ''[[tremissis]]'' of Theudebert II minted at Clermont]]\n'''Theudebert II''' ({{Lang-fr|Thibert ou Th\u00e9odebert}}) (c.585-612),{{sfn|Murray|2018|p=1494}} King of [[Austrasia]] (595\u2013612 [[AD]]), was the son and heir of [[Childebert II]]. He received the kingdom of Austrasia plus the cities (''civitates'') of [[Poitiers]], [[Tours]], [[Le Puy-en-Velay]], [[Bordeaux]], and [[Ch\u00e2teaudun]], as well as the [[Champagne (historical province)|Champagne]], the [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne]], and [[Alamannia|Transjurane Alemannia]].\n\nDuring his early years, his grandmother [[Brunhilda of Austrasia|Brunhilda]] ruled for Theudebert and his brother [[Theuderic II]], who had received the realm of Burgundy. After the two brothers reached adulthood, there were often at war, with Brunhilda siding with Theuderic. In 599, Theuderic defeated Theudebert at [[Sens]], but then the two brothers allied against their cousin [[Chlothar II]] and defeated him at [[Dormelles]] (near [[Montereau-Fault-Yonne|Montereau]]), thereby laying their hands on a great portion of [[Neustria]] (600&ndash;604). At this point, however, the two brothers took up arms against each other; Theuderic defeated Theudebert at [[\u00c9tampes]] and he refused to aid his brother when Theuderic's kingdom was invaded by Clothar II in 605. In 610, he{{who|date=April 2020}} extorted [[Alsace]] from his brother and Theuderic took up arms against him, yet again.\n\nTheudebert was defeated handily by Theuderic at [[Toul]] and at [[Z\u00fclpich]] in 612.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=A09WDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1494&lpg=PA1494&dq=Theudebert+II&source=bl&ots=8viJoJdIou&sig=BxleQHcc-Cljo79zPwcTrsIR-7c&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiwsrmay7rbAhUEvFkKHRKzCiw4FBDoAQg1MAI#v=onepage&q=Theudebert%20II&f=false McCollum, Adam Carter. \"Theudebert II\", ''The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity'', (Oliver Nicholson, ed.), Oxford University Press, 2018], {{ISBN|9780192562463}}</ref><ref>Laury Sarti, ''Perceiving War and the Military in Early Christian Gaul (ca. 400\u2013700 A.D.)'', [[Brill Publishers]],