ER [[WP:NFF]] AND [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eckardt, Stephanie (2017 June). \"Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker\", ''W''. retrieved from https://www.wmagazine.com\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|5637553}}\n* {{Instagram|lauraharrier}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/laura-harrier-louis-vuitton-spiderman-paris-fashion-week-front-row|title=Spiderman\u2019s Laura Harrier Breaks Out in All Black at Louis Vuitton|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrier, Laura}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laura Harrier\n| image              = Laura Harrier Cannes 2018 2.jpg\n| caption            = Harrier at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].\n| birth_name         = <!-- Do NOT add unless sourced to a [[WP:RS]] -->\nLaura Ruth Harrier\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1990|3|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[William Esper Studio]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*model\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Laura Ruth Harrier'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5637553/|title=Laura Harrier|website=IMDb|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B19ityegF54/|title=LAURA HARRIER\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cbaby laura\u2019s first modeling card \ud83d\udc7c\ud83c\udffd i think i was 14? i was so self conscious because i had recently tripped and fell and my lip got\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> (born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle>{{cite web |author=Chang, Mahalia |date=July 3, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/laura-harrier-spiderman-facts-13641 |title=Everything You Need To Know About \u2018Spider-Man\u2019 Babe, Laura Harrier |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>) is an American actress and former model. Harrier was first recognized for her portrayal of [[Destiny Evans]] in the short-lived reboot of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2013. In 2017, she made her major film debut and breakthrough portraying [[Liz Allan|Liz]]<!-- Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked. --><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Laura Harrier confirmed in July 2017 in an interview with ''Total Film'' that the character goes by her mother's maiden name \"Allan\" within the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and that the character would become [[Firestar (comics)|Firestar]] in a future film.</ref> in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Ethan|date=July 25, 2016|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/spider-man-homecoming-characters/|title=Spider-Man Homecoming Characters Revealed|publisher=[[/Film]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/spider-man-homecoming-casts-laura-harrier-from-one-life-to-live-exclusive/|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming' Casts Laura Harrier From 'One Life to Live' (Exclusive)|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|author=Geier, Thom|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tony-revolori-and-laura-harrier-join-spider-man-homecoming-1201754866/|title=Tony Revolori and Laura Harrier Join 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=April 16, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarrier was born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle/> in Chicago, Illinois,<ref name=ABCChicago>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/entertainment/laura-harrier-star-of-spiderman-homecoming-returns-to-chicago/2127314/|title=Laura Harrier, star of 'Spiderman: Homecoming' returns to Chicago|date=June 21, 2017|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]}}</ref> and was raised in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=ABCChicago/> She is biracial with an African-American father and a Caucasian mother.<ref name=TheCut>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/07/laura-harrier-of-spider-man-homecoming-interviewed.html|title=Laughing and Crying With Laura Harrier, the New Star of ''Spider-Man''|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|The Cut]]|author=Weatherford, Ashley|date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> Her father works in insurance and her mother is a speech pathologist.<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|author=Ortved, John|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/laura-harrier/|title=Laura Harrier|magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/film/laura-harrier-interview-balance-not-symmetry-spike-lee-a4201151.html|title=Laura Harrier: 'It's crazy people are surprised films with black people in do well'|date=2019-07-30|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> She has one younger brother.<ref name=\"TheCut\" /> She attended [[Evanston Township High School]] from 2004 to 2008. She began modeling at the age of 17 after coming home from school and being discovered by a photographer who was doing a photo shoot at her house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flaunt.com/content/laura-harrier|title=LAURA HARRIER|website=Flaunt Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/ct-redeye-laura-harrier-interview-spiderman-homecoming-20170629-story.html|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming's' Laura Harrier is no damsel in distress|last=Bostedt|first=Shelbie Lynn|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating high school, Harrier moved to New York City to study art at the [[New York University]] [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://video.wmagazine.com/story/laura-harrier-spider-man-homecoming-feminist-mary-jane/amp/|title=Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker|website=W Magazine Videos|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Upon arrival, Harrier deferred enrollment at the university to continue pursuing modeling.<ref name=TheCut/> Eventually, she found that modeling wasn't fulfilling and decided to pursue acting. She took classes at the [[William Esper Studio]] to study acting.<ref name=Interview/><ref name=TheCut/> \n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nHarrier starred in the reboot of American soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'' as [[Destiny Evans]] in 2013. Her next projects were small roles in the TV series [[Unforgettable (American TV series)|''Unforgettable'']] and in the films ''[[The Last Five Years]]'' and ''[[4th Man Out]]''. In 2014, she was cast in the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] pilot ''Galyntine'', opposite [[Alycia Debnam-Carey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focusfeatures.com/blackkklansman/bio/laura-harrier|title=Laura Harrier Biography - BlacKkKlansman {{!}} Focus Features|last=|first=|date=|website=Laura Harrier as\u00a0Patrice Dumas {{!}} BlacKkKlansman Movie {{!}} Focus Features|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The pilot was canceled and never aired.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amc-passes-drama-pilots-knifeman-745408|title=AMC Passes on Drama Pilots 'Knifeman,' 'Galyntine'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In 2015, she was cast in the [[Steve McQueen (director)|Steve McQueen]] miniseries for [[HBO]], ''[[Codes of Conduct]].''<ref name=\":0\" /> The pilot was filmed however the series was canceled and never aired.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/laura-harrier-codes-of-conduct-cast-steve-mcqueen-1201496352/|title=Laura Harrier Joins Steve McQueen\u2019s \u2018Codes of Conduct\u2019|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2015-05-14|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/steve-mcqueen-tv-is-bad-hbo-netflix/|title=Steve McQueen Says TV \u201cHad Its Moment\u201d & Gets Candid about His Cancelled HBO Series|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=2018-10-26|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Harrier had her major film debut and breakthrough playing [[Peter Parker]]'s love interest [[Liz Allan|Liz]] in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''. In June 2017, it was announced that Harrier would be portraying Millie Montag in HBO's film adaptation of acclaimed novel ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', opposite [[Michael B. Jordan]];<ref name=\"F451_1\">{{cite web|author=Petski, Denise|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/fahrenheit-451-laura-harrier-cast-millie-hbo-movie-1202120406/amp/|title='Fahrenheit 451': Laura Harrier Cast As Millie In HBO Movie |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 2017}}</ref> however, she was later cut from the film.<ref name=\"F451_2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blackkklansman-star-laura-harrier-going-spider-mans-homecoming-cannes-red-carpet/|title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Star Laura Harrier on Going From Spider-Man\u2019s Homecoming to Cannes Red Carpet|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Harrier co-starred as a civil rights activist in the thriller film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]'', opposite [[John David Washington]], [[Adam Driver]], and [[Topher Grace]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Adam Driver Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Black Klansman\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/adam-driver-spike-lee-black-klansman-1202194537/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 May 2018|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Harrier starred in ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/laura-harrier-bria-vinaite-lily-newmark-board-balance-not-symmetry-with-biffy-clyro-exclusive/5133310.article|title=Laura Harrier, Bria Vinaite, Lily Newmark board 'Balance, Not Symmetry' with Biffy Clyro (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>, which was a critical failure.<ref>{{Citation|title=Balance, Not Symmetry (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/balance_not_symmetry|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Clarke|first=Cath|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/aug/01/balance-not-symmetry-review-biffy-clyro-art-school-bria-vinaite-simon-neil|title=Balance, Not Symmetry review \u2013 Biffy Clyro art-school drama topples into cliche|date=2019-08-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She will next star in the upcoming miniseries [[Hollywood (American TV series)|''Hollywood'']] as up-and-coming actress Camille Washington during the [[Hollywood Golden Age]] in the post-[[World War II]] era, alongside [[Darren Criss]], [[David Corenswet]], and [[Samara Weaving]]. The series is set to premiere on [[Netflix]] on May 1, 2020 and is created by [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/dylan-mcdermott-samara-weaving-jim-parsons-maude-apatow-joe-mantello-ryan-murphy-netflix-series-hollywood-1202746400/|title=\u2018Hollywood\u2019: Dylan McDermott, Samara Weaving, Jim Parsons, Maude Apatow & Joe Mantello Among Netflix Series Cast Additions|last=Petski|first=Nellie Andreeva,Denise|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2019-09-27|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=Petski|first3=Denise}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/04/inside-ryan-murphys-hollywood-a-revisionist-homage-to-golden-age-tinseltown|title=Inside Ryan Murphy\u2019s Hollywood, a Revisionist Homage to Golden Age Tinseltown|last=Miller|first=Julie|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n===Modeling and fashion===\nHarrier has modeled for campaigns with companies such as [[Garnier]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[Aldo Group|ALDO]], [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]], and [[L'Or\u00e9al]], and has turned up on the pages of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.<ref name=\"TheCut\" /><ref name=\"Elle\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.byrdie.com/laura-harrier-acne-treatments|title=The 5 Products Actress Laura Harrier Swears By to Fight Acne|last=Bowen|first=Alyss|website=Byrdie|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://models.com/work/aldo-shoes-aldo-shoes-ss-16|title=Aldo Shoes S/S 16 (Aldo)|website=MODELS.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Harrier starred alongside [[Rowan Blanchard]] and [[Mahershala Ali]] in ''The Realest Real'', a short film for luxury French fashion brand [[Kenzo (brand)|Kenzo]] directed by [[Carrie Brownstein]]. Harrier is currently part of [[Calvin Klein]] and [[Louis Vuitton]] campaigns and is an ambassador for luxury Italian jewelry brand [[Bvlgari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|title=Basel World|publisher=[[Bulgari]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235801/https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHarrier has been dating American basketball player [[Klay Thompson]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/everything-you-should-know-about-nba-star-klay-thompsons-girlfriend-laura-harrier.html/|title=Everything You Should Know About NBA Star Klay Thompson's Girlfriend Laura Harrier|last=Winifred|first=Dirk|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-14|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=December 14|first3=2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/warriors/article/klay-thompson-gq-travel-essentials-list-14910738.php|title=Laura Harrier had some thoughts on boyfriend Klay Thompson's 'essentials' list|last=Dowd|first=Katie|last2=SFGATE|date=2019-12-16|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Denotes films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes projects that have not yet been released\n|}\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT add \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Five Years (film)|The Last Five Years]]''\n| Manuscript Woman\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[4th Man Out]]''\n| Dorothy Cuda\n| \n|-\n|2016\n|''The Realest Real''\n|Abby\n|Short film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Liz Allan|Liz]]<!-- Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked. -->\n| \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n| Patrice Dumas\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''\n| Caitlin Walker<!-- According to IMDb she's credited as playing Shirley/Caitlin Walker which might confuse people. In the film's end credits, she's credited as playing Caitlin Walker. This is why on this Wikipedia page we've put Harrier's role as Caitlin Walker because it's the official role name in the film. -->\n| \n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Bios (film)|Bios]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The Starling]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n|''[[One Life to Live]]''\n|[[Destiny Evans]]\n| Main role\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Unforgettable (American TV series)|''Unforgettable'']]\n|Amber\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2014\n|''Galyntine''\n|Wylie\n|Pilot (unaired)\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Codes of Conduct]]''\n|Unknown\n|Pilot (unaired)\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Fahrenheit 451 (2018 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n|Millie Montag\n|Television film; deleted scenes<ref name=\"F451_1\" /><ref name=\"F451_2\" />\n|-\n|2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''{{dagger}}\n|Camille Washington\n|Main role; Post-production\n|}<!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING THAT ISN'T PRESENTLY FILMING OR IN POST-PRODUCTION PER [[WP:NFF]] AND [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eckardt, Stephanie (2017 June). \"Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker\", ''W''. retrieved from https://www.wmagazine.com\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|5637553}}\n* {{Instagram|lauraharrier}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/laura-harrier-louis-vuitton-spiderman-paris-fashion-week-front-row|title=Spiderman\u2019s Laura Harrier Breaks Out in All Black at Louis Vuitton|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrier, Laura}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Harrier"}
{"title_page": "Edison Awards", "text_new": "{{For|the Dutch award given for musical achievement|Edison Award}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = Edison Awards\n| current_awards =\n| image = Edison_Awards_Logo.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| description = Honoring excellence in new product and service development, marketing, human-centered design and innovation.\n| presenter = \n| country = [[United States]]\n| location =top paragraph\n| year = 1987\n| year2 =\n| website = http://www.edisonawards.com/\n}}  \n'''Edison Awards''' is a company that runs an annual competition honoring excellence in innovation in a broad range of categories. \n\n==Company==\n\nThe Edison Awards were established by the [[American Marketing Association]] in 1987, and were spun off as an independent enterprise in 2008.<ref name=Sprouse/>\nAccording to [[crunchbase]], Edison Awards is a private, for-profit company with less than ten employees.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/edison-awards#section-overview |accessdate=2020-04-10 |title=Edison Awards |work=crunchbase}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\nThe Edison Awards are named after the inventor [[Thomas Edison]]. \nThey honor innovations in product and service development, marketing and human-centered design.<ref>{{citation |url=https://gopro.com/pt/st/news/max-wins-edison-award-2020 |accessdate=2020-04-11 |title=MAX TAKES HOME SILVER IN 2020 EDISON AWARDS |publisher=GoPro |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nCategories range from green technology to medical breakthroughs.<ref name=HuffP2011/>\nAs of November 2009 there was a $350 fee for submissions, which must identify how the entrants meet the judging criteria and the innovation competencies defined in the book ''Innovate Like Edison: The Success System of America's Greatest Inventor'' (Gelb & Caldicott 2007).<ref name=Sprouse>{{citation |url=https://science.howstuffworks.com/edison-awards4.htm |accessdate=2020-04-11 |title=How the Edison Awards Work |author=Elizabeth Sprouse |work=How Stuff Works}}</ref>\nThe Edison Award steering committee filters nominations, which are then voted on by a large panel drawn from business and academia.<ref name=PCMagMusk/>\nEntries are judged based on societal impact, marketplace creativity and success.<ref name=HuffP2011>{{citation |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/edison-awards-innovation_b_846402 |accessdate=2020-04-11 |author=Sebastian Howard |author2=Clare Richardson |title=Your Substantive Awards Show: 2011 Edison Awards Honor Innovation in Technology|date=April 7, 2011|work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\nIn 2013, there were 14 categories and 38 sub-categories, with 131 award recipients.<ref>{{citation |url=https://techli.com/edison-awards-highlight-innovation-across-american-industry-titans/45250/ |accessdate=2020-04-11 |title=Edison awards highlight innovation across American industry titans |date=April 26, 2013 |author=Sonali Basak |work=Techli}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n\nPast recipients of the Edison Achievement Award include:\n{{cols|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n* 1991 \u2013 Herb Baum \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/08/22/business/profile-herbert-m-baum-quaker-state-s-quick-change-artist.html |title=Profile: Herbert M. Baum; Quaker State's Quick-Change Artist |author=Agis Salpukas |date=August 22, 1993 |work=New York Times |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n* 1991 \u2013 [[Frank Perdue]] \u2013 Perdue Farms\n* 1992 \u2013 [[William McGowan]] \u2013 MCI Corporation\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Bill_Marriott |J. Willard Marriott, Jr.]] \u2013 Marriott International\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Jay Van Andel]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Raymond W. Smith]] \u2013 Bell Atlantic\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Rich DeVos]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n* 1994 \u2013 Bert C. Roberts \u2013 MCI Corporation\n* 1994 \u2013 H. John Greeniaus \u2013 Nabisco, Inc.\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Arthur C. Martinez|Arthur Martinez]] \u2013 Sears, Roebuck & Co.\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Robert Palmer (computer businessman)|Robert Palmer]] \u2013 Digital Corporation\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Douglas Ivester]] \u2013 Coca-Cola Company\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Nolan D. Archibald]] \u2013 Black & Decker\n* 1997 \u2013 Reuben Mark \u2013 Colgate-Palmolive\n* 1997 \u2013 [[Martha Stewart]] \u2013 MSL Omnimedia\n* 1999 \u2013 Dale Morrison \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n* 1999 \u2013 [[Ted Turner]] \u2013 Time Warner\n* 2009 \u2013 [[David M. Kelley]] \u2013 IDEO\n* 2009 \u2013 [[Susan Desmond-Hellmann]] \u2013 Genentech\n* 2010 \u2013 [[A.G. Lafley]] \u2013 Procter & Gamble\n* 2010 \u2013 [[Susan Hockfield]] \u2013 MIT\n* 2011 \u2013 [[Alan Mulally]] \u2013 Ford Motor Company\n* 2011 \u2013 [[John S. Hendricks]] \u2013 Discovery Communications\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]] \u2013 TED\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Steve Jobs]] \u2013 Apple, Inc.\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Paul E. Jacobs]] \u2013 Qualcomm\n* 2014 \u2013 [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 Tesla, SpaceX<ref name=PCMagMusk>{{citation |author=Damon Poeter |work=PCMag.com |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2457459,00.asp |title=Edison Awards Honor Elon Musk, Lenovo's Yang Yuanqing |date=May 2, 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 [[Yang Yuanqing]] \u2013 Lenovo<ref>Miguel Helft, [http://fortune.com/2014/05/02/in-pursuit-of-innovation-a-milestone-for-lenovo/?section=magazines_fortune \"In pursuit of Innovation, a milestone for Lenovo\"], ''Fortune.com'', May 2, 2014</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 [[Clayton M. Christensen]] \u2013 Harvard Business School\n* 2015 \u2013 [[Robert A. Lutz]] \u2013 General Motors Company\n* 2016 \u2013 [[John T. Chambers|John Chambers]] \u2013 Cisco Systems, Inc.\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Astro Teller]] \u2013 X\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Jeff Immelt]] \u2013 General Electric\n* 2018 \u2013 [[Marillyn Hewson]] \u2013 Lockheed Martin\n* 2019 - [[Ginni Rometty]] \u2013 IBM\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American awards]]\n[[Category:Engineering awards]]\n[[Category:Design awards]]\n[[Category:Business and industry awards]]\n", "text_old"